INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_af_active_11z$$, 2027, $$Provides funding for installation support functions, engineering, and environmental programs in support of Air Force installations including the U.S. Air Force
Academy. The program sustains mission capability, enhances quality of life, enables workforce productivity, and provides infrastructure support. Significant categories of
support are listed below.

Unaccompanied Personnel Housing (UPH) Services
UPH Services include management and execution of government-owned, leased, contracted, or privatized UPH. Unaccompanied Personnel Housing includes Permanent
Party UPH services management, initial issue of furnishings (furniture, appliances, and equipment) for newly constructed and renovated facilities, and management of
replacement furnishings (repair, replace, control, moving and handling, inventory, warehousing, and disposal).

Child and Youth Programs
This category assists Department of War (DoW) military and civilian personnel in balancing the competing demands of family life and accomplishment of the DoW mission
by managing and delivering a system of quality, available, and affordable programs and services (child development, school age, and youth program services) for eligible
children and youth from birth through 18 years of age.

Warfighter and Family Services
Provides principal mission readiness resources for leaders at all levels, service members and their families, qualifying DoW personnel and their families, deployed civilians,
and military retirees and their families by offering information, education, prevention and intervention, and services necessary to address the unique personal and family
readiness needs of the mobile and/or deployed military community.

Morale, Welfare and Recreation (MWR)
Provides appropriated fund resources for all Category A activities (Mission-Sustaining Activities) in support of programs that promote the physical and mental well-being of
military members, their families, and other authorized users. Provides appropriated fund resources for some Category B activities (Community Support Programs) in
support of programs, closely related to mission sustaining programs, which satisfy the physiological and psychological needs of military members, their families, and other
authorized users. Provides appropriated fund resources for minimal Category C activities (Revenue-Generating Programs) in support of programs at designated remote
and isolated locations as defined and authorized.

Lodging
Includes Temporary Duty (TDY) Lodging and Permanent Change of Station (PCS) Lodging. It provides resources for lodging and related services to authorized TDY
personnel to support mission readiness and maintain maximum occupancy in DoW facilities to reduce official travel costs. As well, it provides resources for lodging and
related services to authorized personnel and family members to support PCS travel and maintain maximum occupancy in DoW facilities to reduce official and personal
travel costs.

Airfield Operations:
Provides contract airfield services for transient U.S. military aircraft and aircrew.

Information Technology (IT)
Includes delivery of services consisting of secure and non-secure fixed voice communications, wireless voice, data and video connectivity services, and video conferencing
services. Provides infrastructure support (design, installation, and maintenance) of special circuits/systems in support of life, safety, and security systems; and monitoring
and control systems. Provides collaboration and messaging services and tools for the workforce to communicate and share information. Provides application and web-
hosting operations and management services. Provides for IT Operations Centers including systems and processes necessary to allow customers to have seamless
access to IT applications and solutions. Provides Desktop Management Support for end-user hardware and software services and tools. Provides Service Desk Support,
Continuity of Operations and Disaster Recovery support, requirements and training for common-user software applications, Information Assurance, and Multimedia and
Visual Information. Provides printing, publication, and duplication services.

The Air Force manages IT using an Enterprise Information Technology (EIT) governance process which provide oversight and management of Air Force enterprise-wide IT
strategies, investment priorities, performance measures, portfolio roadmaps, and risks.

Command Support
Includes Wing command staff agency functions formerly part of Base Operating Support (BOS) such as Command Management, Inspector General, Plans and Programs,
Public Affairs, Judge Advocate General, Financial Management, Procurement, Chaplain Ministries, Ground, Flight and Weapons Safety.

Collateral Equipment
Provides procurement of furniture, fixtures, and other furnishings associated with Facilities Restoration and Modernization projects, including projects in the Military
Construction program. This does not include dormitory and housing furnishings.

Civilian Personnel Services
Includes planning, management, coordination, and execution of Civilian Personnel Services for the life-cycle management of human capital at installations for the
Appropriated Fund civilian workforce, military personnel and their families.

Military Personnel Services
Provides customer support services that directly provide or indirectly result in tangible benefits to the military community or the mission. Provides military personnel
information system customer support services. Includes processing workforce changes required to accomplish the DoW mission.

Installation Law Enforcement (LE) Operations
Includes enforcement of federal, state and military law and installation guidance; issuance of citations, detaining suspects, motor vehicle traffic management, traffic
investigations, apprehension and restraint of offenders, and crowd control; crime prevention, crime detection, LE patrols, LE liaison, apprehension of persons who commit
crimes on the installation; testifying in prosecution cases; and temporary detention of offenders. This includes protecting, defending, and deterring against criminal
activities, conduct of minor investigations, the development of plans for the employment of LE activities and functions that include all processes intended to preserve the
principles of law through various strategies.

Installation Physical Security Protection and Services
Includes personnel, procedures, and equipment measures employed or designed to safeguard personnel, facilities, and property from loss, destruction, espionage,
terrorism, or sabotage on the installation; and prevent unauthorized access to facilities, installations, restricted areas, equipment, and materials. This includes regulation of
people, material, and vehicles entering or exiting a designated area; mobile and static security activities for the protection of installation or government assets; conduct of
physical security inspections and assessments; construction design reviews; special protection of high value or sensitive property and management of installation security
systems, plans and funding.

Supply Logistics
Includes eight classes of supply: Class I-Subsistence; Class II-Clothing, individual equipment, and tools; Class III-Petroleum, oils, lubricants; Class IV-Construction
materiel; Class VI-Personal demand items; Class VII-Major end items; Class IX-Repair parts and components; and Class X-Material to support non-military programs.

Community Logistics
Includes the execution of installation food services, laundry, and dry cleaning services. Installation food services includes the operation and administration of installation,
remote, flight and ground support feeding; but excludes the cost of food, costs of non-installation field support, hospital food services, and Basic Allowances for
Subsistence. Laundry and dry cleaning services includes cleaning and pressing textiles, garments, linens and other fabrics. Also, includes organizational clothing and
individual equipment, other articles required by installation, and the sewing on of rank and unit patches on a service member's initial issue of clothing.

Transportation Logistics
Includes management and administration of acquisition dispatch, operation, maintenance, and disposal of all non-tactical government owned and controlled vehicles and
transportation related equipment used for the day-to-day support of installation operations.

Environmental Conservation and Compliance
Provides for protection and enhancement of natural and cultural resources; consultations with environmental regulators; mapping and planning support systems.
Environmental Compliance ensures all federal, state, and local environmental laws are enforced. This is accomplished through sampling, analysis and monitoring;
hazardous waste characterization and disposal; underground storage tank removal, repair, and replacement; leak detection and monitoring; spill response and clean-up;
environmental surveys; training; and maintenance, repair and minor construction projects for environmental facilities and infrastructure.

Pollution Prevention
Established to prevent future pollution by reducing hazardous material use and release of pollutants into the environment as near zero as feasible to alleviate
environmentally harmful discharges to the air, land, surface and ground water.

Facilities Operation
Covers a multitude of critically essential services. Funds mission capability through continuous daily services by purchasing utility commodities such as electricity, natural
gas, drinking water, and sewage removal or by internally producing essential utility commodities through central plant operations. Addresses critical infrastructure needs
through Power Purchase Agreements (PPAs), Energy Savings Performance Contracts (ESPCs), and Utility Energy Service Contracts (UESCs) by upgrading aging

systems and implementing energy-efficient and resilient technologies to improve mission assurance and readiness. Moreover, Utilities Privatization (UP) provides robust
and complex infrastructure improvements for critical missions with cost savings and budget predictability. Requirements demonstrate commitment to resilient and cost
savings infrastructure, while ensuring long-term viability and support for mission and national security. Further, it provides essential human life safety and protection
through activities such as Fire and Emergency Services (911 emergency control centers, fire protection, structural firefighting, aircraft crash rescue, and first responder
capabilities); trash and refuse collection, removal, and disposal; cleaning, sanitizing, and bathroom resupply of publicly accessed, administrative, mission, and community
support buildings through custodial services; clears snow and ice from roads and airfields; protects aircraft hazards through airfield and street sweeping operations;
maintains natural infrastructure (airfield bird hazard management, grass, hazardous trees, weeds control, and wildlife) through grounds maintenance and entomology;
code compliance such as cleaning food service hood and ducts, oil/water separators, lift stations, and performing inspections, and certifications on elevators and
escalators, ground fuel tanks, cranes and hoists attached to real property, and fire alarms. Supports Base Operating Support (BOS) and Base Maintenance Contract
(BMC) annual requirements. Provides Geospatial Engineering capabilities, enterprise information sharing and management capabilities, and facility-related industrial
control system operations, maintenance and associated control system cybersecurity measures. Additionally, provides engineering operations, engineering services, and
real property management required to support municipal-type activities and includes real property leases to meet mission needs.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Air Force/FY27 Air Force Operation & Maintenance Volume I.pdf$$, 176, 180, $$02565dc447d4f0fc3d98f0c4166bb342f5fbc3c89064994e817ec530fe7113d7$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_dla_umbrella$$, 2026, $$The Defense Logistics Agency's (DLA's) mission is to "Drive and sustain Warfighter readiness by delivering unmatched global support as the
Nation's Logistics Combat Support Agency." As the Nation's Combat Logistics Support Agency and valued partner, DLA is innovative, adaptable,
agile, and accountable and focused on the Warfighter Always. The DLA is predominately a working capital funded agency, however, DLA's O&M
programs in direct support of strategic readiness include:
    • Warstopper: Implements industrial preparedness measures for critical go-to war requirements. Identifies and addresses supply chain
         vulnerabilities, and enables surge capabilities.
             o Mapping: As DoD's Integrated Materiel Manager & Distributor of 70K map items, DLA provides nearly 250K hydrographic,
                 topographic, and aeronautical map products (23,500 classified).
             o Generalized Emulation of Microcircuits: Sources non-procurable military grade microcircuits to keep legacy weapon systems
                 operational.
    • DoD Enterprise Business Systems (DEBS): Provides operational support for DEBS, such as the Defense Agencies Initiative, Joint
         Contingency Contracting System, and Standard Procurement System.
    • Logistic Support Activities (Classified Program): Provides specialized logistics support to DoD's national-level objectives.

Overall Assessment
The Defense Agencies Initiative (DAI) and Family and Morale, Welfare and Recreation (FMWR) benefit from significant increases. For DAI, new
Tier II Help Desk initiatives were introduced to meet the rising demand for user support. Additional funding will enable key system enhancements
to accommodate a growing user base, bolster audit-related capabilities, and ensure full technical compliance with the Federal Financial
Management Improvement Act. For FMWR, increased funding will accelerate the implementation and staffing of the Lead Educator and Special
Needs Inclusion Coordinator roles. The funding also expands childcare discounts at DoD facilities. These increases were offset by reductions to
other Operation and Maintenance (O&M) programs resulting in a net change in the O&M topline. Programs absorbing decreases include
Contingency Logistics and Warstopper; this is driven by anticipated efficiencies in the area of contract services reflecting a renewed effort to
streamline operations.$$, NULL, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/DW/OM_Volume1_Part1.pdf$$, 30, 30, $$ba3469b04647e4f7da6e949f09ee674de1cbb1080042a52c9c2e0ae2f6cb17a4$$, $$2026-05-09T21:54:52.835832+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_socom_prodev$$, 2026, $$A. 3EV8 - Professional Development Education - Includes the Joint Special Operations University (JSOU) at MacDill Air Force Base, FL, the
    U.S. Air Force Special Operations School (USAFSOS) at Hurlburt Field, FL, and the Naval Special Warfare Leadership Education and
    Development (NLEAD) Command at San Diego, CA. The JSOU is an institution of higher learning consisting of teaching and research
    facilities focused on producing Joint Special Operations strategic and operational analysis and education. As a Joint Special Operations
    Center of Excellence, JSOU is dedicated to building and maintaining a consortium of Joint special operations specialized learning activities
    focused on professional development of SOF leaders as well as non-SOF decision makers at the intermediate and senior levels. The
    USAFSOS offers education in irregular warfare, regional studies and cultural awareness, SOF professional development to educate Air
    Commandos, the special operations community, services, and other U.S. Government agencies. The NLEAD Command provides SOF
    education and leadership growth for platoon leaders, lead petty officers, career counselors, and command leaders.$$, NULL, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/DW/OM_Volume1_Part1.pdf$$, 847, 847, $$237df38432332b4a77cce5c66d0967821589638a951cecd3608453fa019f200b$$, $$2026-05-09T21:54:52.835832+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_sisc_umbrella$$, 2026, $$The Support for International Sporting Competitions, Defense (SISC) account is funded with a no-year appropriation that provides continuing
Department of Defense (DoD) support to national and international sporting events that are either certified by the Attorney General or supports
specific organizations, such as: the Special Olympics, Paralympics, and the United States Olympic and Paralympic Committees (USOPC) through
the Paralympic Military Program.

The Department is not requesting any appropriated funds in FY 2026 due to the available balances in the account from the DoD Appropriations
Acts for FY 2015 and FY 2023. In FY 2025, the Department is supporting 19 Paralympic sporting events sanctioned by the USOPC through the
Paralympic Military Program with an estimated cost of $1 million. In FY 2026, the Department intends to support approximately 24 sporting events
with an estimated cost of $2.7 million. The International Sporting Competitions planning cycles do not fully align with the DoD budget cycle, which
can result in year of execution requests for support.

These funds support safety, security and logistical requirements for certain sporting competitions. Under the provisions of 10 U.S.C. Section
2564, the Department has the authority to assist Federal, state and/or local agencies in support of civilian sporting events if the Attorney General
certifies that such assistance is necessary to meet essential security and safety needs.

The Department can also provide support to the Special Olympics, the Paralympics, a sporting event sanctioned by the U.S. Olympic and
Paralympic Committee, through the Paralympic Military Program, and/or any national or international Paralympic sporting event that meet
requirements outlined in 10 U.S.C. Section 2564, as amended by Public Law (P.L.) 110-181 Section 372. Support for these events are eligible for
DoD support and exempt from Attorney General certification.$$, NULL, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/DW/OM_Volume1_Part_2.pdf$$, 126, 127, $$196ca20894fc9bb8733d77c8d9674d276736719d84db6ecd83b9b689e5f6b780$$, $$2026-05-09T21:54:52.835832+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_classified_9999$$, 2026, $$Classified line item (DefWide BA-04). The CLASSIFIED 9999 SAG aggregates intelligence community and other classified O&M activities under the Defense-Wide appropriation that are not separately disclosed in the public budget. Per-line detail is reported only in the classified annex.

