INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_dsca_umbrella$$, 2027, $$The Defense Security Cooperation Agency (DSCA), in coordination with the Office of the Under
Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment (OUSW(A&S)) and the Office of the Under Secretary of War for Policy (OUSW(P)), leads the
security cooperation enterprise in delivering effective, enduring, and timely solutions that support national security, defense strategic guidance
and mutual U.S. and partner interests.

Consistent with the 2026 National Defense Strategy (NDS), the FY 2027 President’s Budget request continues to align and deliver security
cooperation programs and efforts in accordance with priorities of the President of the United States and Secretary of War’s (SecWar) priorities.
These efforts include the day-to-day operations of the DSCA headquarters, the Defense Security Cooperation University (DSCU), the
Department of War (DoW) Regional Centers for Security Studies, and the Defense Security Cooperation Service (DSCS). Under the provisions
of the Title 10 U.S.C. Chapter 16, the FY 2027 budget request will continue to support the execution of a Department-wide framework for the
assessment, monitoring, and evaluation of security cooperation activities and continue to implement a workforce development program targeting
all DoW professionals supporting security cooperation efforts. The DSCA will continue to execute Department of State security assistance
programs and activities in accordance with the Foreign Assistance Act and the Arms Export and Control Act. Additionally, the DSCA budget
request supports program management and administration of the Humanitarian Assistance, Foreign Disaster Relief, and Humanitarian Mine
Action programs funded within the Overseas Humanitarian, Disaster and Civic Aid appropriation.

The DSCA plans, directs, implements, administers, and provides guidance for the execution of assigned security cooperation programs and
activities and facilitates the planning, implementation, monitoring, and evaluation of security cooperation activities funded through the DSCA.
The DSCA activities encourage and enable foreign partners to responsibly act in support of U.S. national security objectives. Security
cooperation activities are often complex and span the phases of conflict from shaping the environment to enabling civil authority activities. The
DSCA collaborates closely with the interagency, geographic combatant commands (CCMD), industry, and partner nations to execute security
cooperation activities. Moreover, the DSCA seeks to maximize security cooperation program effectiveness.

CAPACITY BUILDING

European Capacity Building
European Capacity Building funds security cooperation programs and activities that build the military capacity of European partners, including
Ukraine, to address shared national security challenges, enhance interoperability among partner forces, and enable European allies and
partners to take on greater responsibility for their own security challenges. These efforts would support U.S. national security and defense
strategic objectives.

                                                                                                                                              DSCA
                                                                         2

                                                    Defense Security Cooperation Agency$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/DW/Vol1_Part1/DSCA_OP-5.pdf$$, 2, 8, $$22435028395ee572bfc73936d402bebb7c6476d02fc47c36d35eb74ac6784044$$, $$2026-05-10T00:59:04.217246+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_dodea_dodde$$, 2027, $$The Department of War Education Activity (DoWEA) provides schooling for children of U.S. military families stationed around the world. DoWEA’s
purpose is to ensure students receive a consistent, high-quality education that prepares them to succeed as responsible citizens. DoWEA
operates under the Department of War and includes the overseas school system, the domestic school system, Management Headquarters, and
Consolidated School Support.

The overseas school system educates 44,779 students in 106 schools across 11 countries: Bahrain, Belgium, Cuba, Germany, Italy, Japan,
Korea, the Netherlands, Spain, Turkey, and the United Kingdom. These schools provide a full Pre-K through 12th-grade program and oversee the
Department’s Virtual High School, which offers online courses to support academic and career goals. Performance is measured through student
achievement, graduation rates, and the ability to maintain continuous school operations in overseas environments.

The domestic school system serves 21,591 students in 53 schools across seven states—Alabama, Georgia, Kentucky, New York, North Carolina,
South Carolina, and Virginia—as well as Guam and Puerto Rico. The program also manages Special Arrangement contracts that fund tuition and
transportation for 1,195 students in locations where the Department does not operate its own schools. These agreements, authorized under Title
10, U.S. Code § 2164, allow local public school districts to educate eligible military-connected students. Current Special Arrangement locations
include Delaware, Massachusetts, New York, and Puerto Rico. Performance is tracked through accurate enrollment, timely tuition payments, and
continuity of student services.

The Non-DoW Schools Program supports 4,999 students whose families serve in remote overseas areas without Department-run schools. Eligible
students receive tuition assistance and other required educational support. The program operates under statutory authority in Title 20, U.S. Code
§ 926(b). Performance is measured through timely tuition processing, verification of student eligibility, and compliance reviews to ensure students
receive appropriate educational services.

Management Headquarters provides system-wide oversight and ensures all schools follow a consistent Pre-K through 12 curriculum. Funding
supports curriculum development, professional development for educators, program evaluations, and monitoring of student performance.
Performance is assessed through accreditation results, curriculum implementation milestones, and educator training completion rates.

                                                                                                                                                             DoDDE
                                                                                  2

                                                          DoD Dependents Education$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/DW/Vol1_Part1/DoWDE_OP-5.pdf$$, 2, 6, $$06376d4d6f6f59c45549f8a13a4195a2d8071b93d5261da616d1b1e5f665f73f$$, $$2026-05-10T00:59:04.217246+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_osd_umbrella$$, 2027, $$The Office of the Secretary of War (OSW) is responsible for policy development, planning, resource management, and program evaluation. The OSW includes the
offices of top civilian Department decision-makers concerning personnel, weapons acquisition, research, intelligence, and fiscal policy, as well as offices that the
Secretary of War (SECWAR) establishes to assist in carrying out assigned responsibilities. The OSW includes the immediate offices of the SECWAR and Deputy
Secretary of War (DEPSECWAR), the Under Secretaries of War, the Principal Staff Assistants (PSA), the Executive Support Offices, and other core programs,
which are listed below:

OSW Offices/Principal Staff Assistants:
• Immediate Office of the Secretary and Deputy Secretary of War
• Office of the Assistant Secretary of War for Legislative Affairs (OASW(LA))
• Office of the Assistant Secretary of War for Special Operations Low-Intensity Conflict (OASW(SO/LIC)) & Secretariat for Special Operations (SSO)
• Office of the Assistant to the Secretary of War for Public Affairs (OATSW(PA))
• Defense Innovation Unit (DIU)
• Director of Administration and Management (DA&M)
• Director, Cost Assessment and Program Evaluation (D, CAPE)
• Director, Operational Test and Evaluation (D, OT&E)
• DoW Chief Information Officer (DoW CIO)
• Office of General Counsel (OGC)
• Office of the Under Secretary of War for Acquisition and Sustainment (OUSW(A&S))
• Office of the Under Secretary of War (Comptroller) (OUSW(C))
• Office of the Under Secretary of War for Intelligence and Security (OUSW(I&S))
• Office of the Under Secretary of War for Personnel and Readiness (OUSW(P&R))
• Office of the Under Secretary of War for Policy (OUSW(P))
• Office of the Under Secretary of War for Research and Engineering (OUSW(R&E))
• Strategic Capabilities Office (SCO)
• Test Resource Management Center (TRMC)

Other Funded Programs and Organizations:
• Civilian Pay

                                                                                                                                                     OSW
                                                                                2

                                                             Office of the Secretary of War$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/DW/Vol1_Part1/OSW_OP-5.pdf$$, 2, 18, $$23c6ce21f797309cc4d685f24b10411f6b9dd8f1cdc45ab80078d0b076070e8c$$, $$2026-05-10T00:59:04.217246+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_whs_umbrella$$, 2027, $$The Washington Headquarters Services (WHS) FY 2027 President’s Budget request of $536,546 thousand is $126,440 thousand above the FY
2026 requested amount and is comprised of $6,956 thousand in pricing increases and a net $119,484 thousand in programmatic increases. The
FY 2027 request empowers the WHS to continue to support key administration initiatives and priorities in defense of the Nation.

The WHS directly supports the Department of War (DoW), the Secretary of War (SECWAR), the Office of the Secretary of War (OSW), the Deputy
Secretary of War (DEPSECWAR), the Defense Legal Services Agency (DLSA), the United States Court of Appeals for the Armed Forces
(USCAAF), the Defense Agencies and DoW Field Activities (DAFA), including Pentagon Force Protection Agency (PFPA), the Defense Security
Cooperation Activity (DSCA), the Defense Prisoner of War (POW)/Missing in Action (MIA) Accounting Agency (DPAA), National Guard Bureau,
Defense Technology Security Administration (DTSA), and Defense Test Resource Management Center (DTRMC) and other select Federal
Agencies such as the Department of State (DoS), the National Archives and Records Administration (NARA), and the White House. Additionally
beginning in FY 2026 WHS began supporting the Direct Reporting Program Managers (DRPM) including the DRPM for Submarines, DRPM for
Golden Dome for America, DRPM for Critical Major Weapons Systems, as well as the Economic Defense Unit. The WHS provides more than 80
essential services, absorbing and consolidating administrative requirements that allow DoW staff to focus on matters involving policy analysis and
program oversight more efficiently. The WHS demonstrates expertise and innovation and provides solutions to tackle complex issues though
operational prioritization. The WHS continues to transform into an organization of the future by focusing and upgrading core functions.

The WHS continues to cultivate the future by investing in the 2026 National Defense Strategy (NDS) objectives of “America First. Peace Through
Strength. Common Sense,” through the following lines of effort:

    1) Defend the Homeland – The WHS provides foundational, mission-critical support that enhances the operational readiness and
       effectiveness of supported stakeholders directly responsible for homeland defense.

    2) Deter China in the Indo-Pacific Through Strength, Not Confrontation – The WHS is a key enabler for supported stakeholders that manage
       strategic alliances, technology security, and inter-agency coordination, all of which are central to the deterrence strategy in the Indo-
       Pacific.
    3) Increase Burden-Sharing with U.S. Allies and Partners – The WHS streamlines administrative and support functions in support of the
       Department by efficiently allocating and maximizing resources, consistently innovating solutions, and providing a skilled workforce.

                                                                                                                                           WHS
                                                                        2

                                                      Washington Headquarters Service$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/DW/Vol1_Part1/WHS_OP-5.pdf$$, 2, 6, $$48b701fe895546064898c182ad814b4515ca3a97b975cf979e8c02b563160a0f$$, $$2026-05-10T00:59:04.217246+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_ctra_umbrella$$, 2027, $$The Cooperative Threat Reduction (CTR) Program enables the Department of War (DoW) to work cooperatively with partner nations to reduce or eliminate the
threat of the proliferation of Weapons of Mass Destruction (WMD) or WMD-related materials. The DoW derives authority to carry out the CTR Program through the
Cooperative Threat Reduction Act (Public Law 113-291), and has used this authority to reduce chemical, biological, and nuclear threats to the United States and
its interests worldwide. To accomplish this, the CTR Program includes several lines of effort: the Biological Threat Reduction Program, the Proliferation Prevention
Program, Global Nuclear Security, Chemical Security Program (formerly Chemical Security and Elimination); and Transportation Elimination Disposition (formerly
Delivery System Threat Reduction). These efforts facilitate the elimination and safe and secure transportation of WMD, weapon components, weapon-related
material, and associated delivery vehicles. They also prevent the proliferation of WMD and WMD-related materials, technology, and expertise.

                                                                                                                           $ in thousands

                                                                                                          FY 2025                  FY 2026                 FY 2027
                                                                                                          Actuals                  Enacted                 Request
A. BIOLOGICAL THREAT REDUCTION PROGRAM                                                                    160,402                  138,565                  66,524

The Biological Threat Reduction Program (BTRP) protects the United States and its Armed Forces from biological threats by strengthening the capabilities of
partner nations to prevent, detect, and prepare for the threat of biological weapons use by an adversary. The program implements activities to prevent the
proliferation of biological weapons; biological weapons components; and biological weapons-related materials, technologies, and expertise. To achieve its national
security mission, the program assists partner nations as they seek to improve their biosafety and biosecurity capabilities to counter biological threats. The BTRP
works cooperatively with countries across Africa, Europe, the Middle East, and Asia to secure pathogen collections and enhance biosafety and biosecurity at
vulnerable sites. The BTRP goals for each partner country and region follow.

Eurasia
CTR will reduce its funding activities in Eurasia and focus on identifying opportunities for CTR to receive funding from European partners and allies to conduct

                                                                                                                                                      OP-5 Exhibit
                                                                                                                                                             CTR

                                                                                 1

                                                              Cooperative Threat Reduction Program$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/DW/Vol1_Part2/CTR_OP-5.pdf$$, 5, 14, $$ca9576e8cdb64e5af7a3194ca41f51cd92cc54c62117e2a0d44aacb0fcec8e39$$, $$2026-05-10T00:59:04.217246+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c4c$$, 2026, $$Anti-Submarine Range and Test Program
SSRNM, FSSN, US FORACS (N96) - The Surface Ship Radiated Noise Measurement (SSRNM), Fleet Sonar Self Noise (FSSN), and United States (U.S.) Fleet Operational
Readiness Accuracy Check Sites (FORACS). The SSRNM program provides acoustic trials, acoustic trial management, acoustic data for fleet tactical plans and vulnerability
assessments of surface combatants that have been constructed with reduced acoustic signature and silencing systems. Noise reduction is necessary to achieve sonar performance,
reduce vulnerability to acoustic influence mines and torpedoes. These funds also provide life cycle support, Technical Direction Agent (TDA) and In-service-Engineering Agent
(ISEA) support for SSRNM in-service systems. The FSSN program provides expert analysis of sonar self-noise data and is part of the ship's Planned Maintenance System (PMS).
The analysis provides data about the ship's sonar operational status and its interaction with other assets. The U.S. FORACS program consists of two fixed test ranges (Atlantic
Undersea Test and Evaluation Center (AUTEC) & San Clemente Island (SCI) in Southern California and deployable capabilities. Mission is to measure the bearing, range,
position, and heading accuracy of sensors in surface ships, submarines, and maritime aircraft to satisfy Sensory Accuracy Test (SAT) requirements material readiness standards
through dynamic combat system performance evaluation. Funding for SATs, Technical Direction Agent (TDA), and In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) support for fixed and
portable SAT capabilities for both government and contractor support.

NATO FORACS & US FORACS (N94)- North Atlantic Treaty Organization Naval Forces Sensor and Weapon Readiness Accuracy Check Sites (NATO FORACS) program is a
multi-national NATO project available to all Alliance nations and consists of three fixed test ranges and deployable capabilities. Mission is to measure the bearing, range, position,
and heading accuracy of sensors in surface ships, submarines, and maritime aircraft to satisfy national requirements and meet NATO material readiness standards through dynamic
combat system performance evaluation. U.S. participation in the NATO FORACS program provides the U.S. cost share for the operation of three test ranges (Norway, Greece,
Atlantic Undersea Test and Evaluation Center (AUTEC)). The U.S. FORACS program has a fixed range off the coast of San Clemente Island (SCI) in Southern California and
provides deployed portable test capabilities to satisfy requirements. Funding for SATs, Technical Direction Agent (TDA), and In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) for both
government and contractor support for fixed and portable Sensor Accuracy Test (SAT) capabilities to both U.S. and NATO FORACS.

UTRE, MK28 (N94)- The Underwater Tracking Range Equipment (UTRE) Program provides pinger systems for tracking on the Navy's Undersea Fleet Training and Test &
Evaluation Ranges. The program provides equipment maintenance, installation, and repair, plus data reporting and support of fleet exercises at the Atlantic Undersea Test &
Evaluation Center (AUTEC), Southern California Offshore Range Extension (SCORE) and Barking Sands Tactical Underwater Range (BARSTUR) training ranges. In addition,
this budget supports product improvement efforts for the tracking instrumentation in support of the Navy's underwater readiness training. This program also provides Technical
Direction Agent (TDA) and In-Service-Engineering Agent (ISEA) support for underwater tracking range equipment. The MK28 Surface Weapon Test Target (SWTT) provides the
Navy the capability to test the explosive train of torpedoes and the reliability of the torpedoes warhead. The funding supports government oversight and product improvement
efforts.

ICS CAP (N97)- The Integrated Combat Systems Certification and Assessment Program (ICS CAP) is a program that determines and certifies the technical, material, and logistical
readiness of the submarine ICS to support operational submarine warfare mission areas. ICS CAP supports certification following initial installation and subsequent modernization
of the ICS for all new construction and in-service submarines. ICS certification for in-service submarines is based on data gathered by the ICS CAP test team from dockside testing
and at-sea testing, as well as the review of other technical documentation. Data to support ICS certification of new construction submarines is provided by the acquisition Program
Office (PMS 450 for VA Class submarines) from Program-sponsored testing, as well as the review of other technical documentation.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 236, 255, $$e60bf9ea1e5c92c30da5e285b6223c9779435cfcf8557f97f33bd54095e11a4c$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c5c$$, 2026, $$Funding within this activity group supports the performance of the Naval Meteorology and Oceanographic mission functions worldwide and provides a wide array of essential
operational meteorological and oceanographic products and services to operating forces afloat and ashore. These services include collecting and processing environmental data
using resources such as oceanographic ships, aircraft, satellites, and computing systems. These products and services enhance the performance of active and passive sensor and
weapon systems; optimize the effectiveness of the sea control mission for mine counter-measures; and identify the environmental effects that influence the performance of fixed
and mobile warfare systems and tactics. Hydrographic data from near shore areas supports the production of coastal, combat, approach, harbor and special purpose nautical charts
used to address littoral warfare requirements. General and tailored oceanographic, acoustic and meteorological forecasts provided daily to fleet commanders and individual
operating units from the Meteorology and Oceanography Command's numerical modeling and forecasting centers and from forecasting support activities located worldwide.
Funding also supports the U.S. Naval Observatory's mission to provide Precise Time and Time Interval (PTTI), Astrometry, Astrometry (Celestial Reference Frame CRF), and
Earth Orientation products to DOD and other government agencies. As DOD's designated PTTI manager, the Naval Observatory maintains the Master Clock, and provides
essential PTTI information to space surveillance, communications, and navigation systems, including the Navigation Satellite Timing & Ranging (NAVSTAR) Global Positioning
System (GPS). Astrometry and Earth Orientation products provide vital support for various strategic and tactical programs including precise targeting and positioning of ballistic
missiles, stellar navigation, and intelligence collection and mapping using satellites.

Oceanographic Ship Operations: All days at sea per year (transit, survey, rescue mission, etc.) as well as all days in port per year (VRA, diplomatic, resupply, etc.) and
Geotechnical analysis support and ISS-60 life cycle support systems.

Oceanographic Collections and Deployments: Meteorological and Oceanographic Support Systems such as Satellite Support and Oceanographic Models; Maritime Homeland
Defense Systems; Exercises; Unmanned Underwater Vehicle (UUV) Deployments; Ocean Products; Acoustic Products; Mine Warfare (MIW) Products; Builder Products; Target
Acquisition Weapon Software (TAWS) Products and METOC Support Products.

Weather & Fleet Safety (Deployable Fleet Support): All facets of weather support to at-sea and shore based naval forces, operations and facilities. This entails aviation weather
forecasting products and services for naval aviation, maritime and tropical weather forecasting and warnings, naval resource protection recommendations and operational warfare
support to Carrier Strike Groups (CSGs) and Amphibious Ready Groups (ARGs).

Operational Environmental Modeling: Supports oceanographic environmental characterization worldwide and provides an array of essential operational oceanographic products
and services to operating forces afloat and ashore and supports the worldwide production and delivery of operational meteorological products and services to Navy/DOD assets
afloat and ashore.

Operational Command, Interagency Liaison and Ed & Training: Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW) and Mine Information Warfare (MIW) direct Fleet support such as
deploying ASW and MIW teams and utilizes reach-back cells. Enables capabilities acoustic models and databases, and collection of oceanographic and geophysical data as
required by COCOM Components. Supports CNO's Undersea Dominance initiatives.

Operational Meteorology and Oceanography: Supports the performance of Naval Meteorological and Oceanographic mission functions worldwide as well as Intelligence
Preparation of the Operational Environment (IPOE) for Information Warfare (associated warfare areas and operations), Safety of Navigation (surface and submarine), Safety of
Flight, and Resource Protection. It also provides funding for In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) and Software Support Activity (SSA) efforts including engineering and logistics
support for all Navy and Marine Corps meteorological equipment. Funding will enable the timely introduction and support of various meteorological and oceanographic equipment
such as Naval Integrated Tactical Environmental System Next Generation (NITES-Next), Marine Corps Meteorological Mobile Facility Replacement Next Generation$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 256, 268, $$d69bbaa23a6deec2b1140c7850e0860a5a779e5ac5d1fe28cf9dec1aa1aae7cf$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_4s56$$, 2027, $$Sub-program of 4B2N (Planning, Engineering, and Program). FY2027 estimate: $0. This sub-activity group (4S56, DON Robotics Transition Support) is a budget line code under the parent SAG; per the FY2027 PB structure (F-NEW-V36-6), sub-program rollups are nested within parent OP-5 narratives and do not have standalone descriptions. Refer to parent SAG 4B2N. Source: O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf parent narrative. synth_subprogram v41.$$, NULL, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, NULL, NULL, $$d61f88755ecd5a785e8b70d0752312f2c8fced05c0d60b4de3979030b3cd68ec$$, $$2026-05-10T01:03:08.635372+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_2a1f$$, 2027, $$The Navy's Sealift Program provides the worldwide capability to deploy combat forces and/or supporting material that may be required to meet national contingency objectives.
This Line Item is divided into three functional areas: (1) Maritime Prepositioning Ships (2) Sealift Program Support and (3) Exercise Support

Maritime Prepositioning Ships (MPS)
Afloat Prepositioning strategically places military equipment and supplies aboard ships located in key ocean areas to ensure rapid availability during a major theater war, a
humanitarian operation or other contingency. Prepositioning ships provide quick and efficient movement of military gear between operating areas without reliance on other
nations' transportation networks. Many prepositioning ships are able to discharge liquid, containerized or motorized cargo both pier side or while anchored offshore by using
floating hoses and shallow-draft watercraft, called lighterage, that are carried aboard. This allows cargo to be ferried to shore in areas where ports are non-existent or in poor
condition and gives the nation's military forces the ability to operate in both developed and undeveloped areas of the world.

MPS provide fleet prepositioning and sea basing ships from strategic bases worldwide. MPS is comprised of 13 different mission ships and are divided into 2 Maritime
Prepositioning Force (MPF) squadrons. Each MPF squadron consists of self-sustaining multi-cargo ships, which provide 30 days of over-the-shore support to Marines. The
flexibility and comprehensive logistical support these ships provide is vital to the Marine Corps' ability to sustain a presence ashore in the early days of emergency/combat
operations in support of Commander, U.S. Indo-Pacific Command.
These ships operate within the Navy Working Capital Fund (NWCF).

Sealift Program Support
The Sealift Support Program Office (SSPO) provides cradle to grave life cycle management for all Amphibious Sealift systems. This function includes development and design of
new or replacement equipment, acquisition of new or recapitalized equipment, maintenance and repair to deployed equipment, and disposal of obsolete equipment. The systems
include: Improved Navy Lighterage System (INLS), Navy Lighterage (NL), Maritime Prepositioning Force (MPF) Utility Boars, Lighter, Amphibious Resupply, Cargo, 5-Ton
(LARC-V), Landing Craft, Mechanized (LCM-8), Elevated Causeway, Modular, Amphibious Bulk Liquid Transfer System (ABLTS), Travel Lifts, Mobil Lighterage Transfer
System (MLTS), and Off Shore Petroleum Discharge System (OPDS).

Exercise Support
Provides funding outside of a working capital fund for exercises of the Aviation Maintenance ships, Prepositioning ships, and the Naval Beach Groups.

MANDATORY FUNDING JUSTIFICATION:

  The FY 26 spend plan amount for Ship Prepositioning and Surge includes $369,408 thousand of discretionary and $3,500 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a
  total of $372,908 thousand.

       388                                                                                                                                                       Exhibit OP-5, 2A1F$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 388, 399, $$5b53bea72f8d89f87e4af5b2ab154378ecdafe07f9f707a333a8f10004c6f441$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c3c$$, 2027, $$This subactivity group includes funding for the Integrated Undersea Surveillance System, Commander, Undersea Surveillance (CUS and the Naval Ocean Processing Facilities
(NOPF)) at Whidbey Island and Dam Neck. Programs include the Sound Surveillance System (SOSUS), Fixed Distributive System (FDS), Fixed Surveillance System (FSS),
International Programs and the Surveillance Towed Array Sensor System (SURTASS).

Tug Auxiliary General Ocean Surveillance (T-AGOS)

Ocean surveillance ships gather underwater acoustical data. The T-AGOS ships are operated by Military Sealift Command to support the anti-submarine warfare mission of the
commanders of the Atlantic and Pacific Fleets. The two classes of surveillance ships use surveillance towed-array sensor system (SURTASS) equipment to gather undersea
acoustic data. The ships also carry electronic equipment to process and transmit that data via satellite to shore stations for evaluation. Victorious-class ocean surveillance ships are
built on a small-waterplane, twin-hull, or SWATH, design for greater stability at slow speeds in high latitudes under adverse weather conditions. Impeccable has a hull form based
on that of Victorious, but has a more powerful propulsion plant and is designed specifically for deploying an additional active towed-array system.

Fixed Surveillance System (SS) Classified Program

Additional details held at a higher classification.

Integrated Undersea Surveillance Systems (IUSS)

Funding in this line supports the Maritime Surveillance Systems (MSS) mission to detect, classify, localize, track and report nuclear and diesel submarines in deep-ocean and
littoral regions. Specifically financed is the Surveillance Towed Array Sensor System (SURTASS) which provides funding for the operation and maintenance of mission
equipment on T-AGOS (Auxiliary General Ocean Surveillance) Class ships (including array depot repairs for passive systems, as well as Low Frequency Active (LFA)/Compact
LFA (CLFA) equipment maintenance), operations and maintenance planning and execution, technician support services (including training), maintenance of Integrated Common
Processor (ICP), and program support. This line funds all support and sustainment efforts for the Expeditionary SURTASS (SURTASS-E) project. OMN funding for both
SURTASS and SURTASS-E supports ship operations, including logistic support facility, array maintenance facility, software maintenance, and depot level spares. Funding will
also continue to provide technical support by US technicians to SURTASS ships and shore facilities in Japan. Funding in this line supports Deployable Surveillance Systems (DSS)
which provides on-demand, deployable maritime surveillance capability in ocean areas of national interest in support of Joint and Naval Task Force Commanders.

Relocatable Over-The-Horizon Radar (ROTHR)

Funds support three systems in use, in Virginia, Texas and Puerto Rico. A unique radar system designed to provide tactical warning to battle group commanders of air and surface
threats at an extended range to allow time for responsive engagement.

Drug Interdiction and Counter Drug Activities

Counter Narcotics funding is provided during the year of execution. Funds support Relocatable Over-the-Horizon Radar (ROTHR) systems. A unique radar system designed to
provide tactical warning to battle group commanders of air and surface threats at an extended range to allow time for responsive engagement.

       201                                                                                                                                                       Exhibit OP-5, 1C3C$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 201, 210, $$e06f745d31a15e285d5fcf0817c831a881019ee26d97d92d16ea4832b895e470$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_2c1h$$, 2027, $$The EXMEDS program provides for the management, transformation, modernization, and reconstitution of platforms that will deliver capabilities that are more agile across the
spectrum of Navy, Marine Corps, and Joint operations. Navy's EHSS funding provides equipment and supplies for EMFs, T-AHs, EMUs, ERSSs, ERCS's and FDPMUs, as well
as program staff at BUMED and Navy Expeditionary Medical Support Command (NEMSCOM).

Expeditionary Health Services Systems (EHSS) provide comprehensive deployable medical systems (DEPMEDS) to U.S. and allied forces in the event of combat or contingency
operations. DEPMEDS includes large, land-based Role 3 Expeditionary Medical Facilities (EMF), Role 3 Hospital Ships (T-AH), smaller land-based Role 2 Enhanced
Expeditionary Medical Units (EMU), very small land or sea-based Role 2 Light Maneuver (R2LM) Expeditionary Resuscitative Surgery Systems (ERSS), and land-based Forward
Deployable Preventive Medicine Units (FDPMU). EMFs and EMUs are pre-positioned ashore and afloat throughout the world and are designed to complement and expand the
organic medical capabilities of the Fleet and play a critical role in the Marine Corps' evolving war fighting strategies of forward deployed theater operations.

The T-AH Hospital Ships, USNS MERCY (T-AH 19) and USNS COMFORT (T-AH 20), afloat have the capability to conduct casualty medical treatment in 12 operation rooms
and 1,000 beds. A Medical Treatment Facility (MTF) is integrated into the hull of each T-AH. The MTFs provide scalable hospitalization for use by Department of War in
support of the full spectrum of medical operations from foreign humanitarian assistance to major combat operations worldwide. The T-AHs are maintained in a five-day Reduced
Operation Status (ROS-5). They have a cadre assigned, are out ported at layberth, and undergo annual sea trials, periodic dock trials, and have periodic regulatory dry dockings
and inspections.
EMFs and EMUs are composed of distinct capability based modules/packages which can be tailored to meet whatever mission is required. These medical and surgical facilities
provide the ability to stabilize, treat, and rehabilitate wounded troops. Funding supports the transformational modernization/upgrading of these units through the Service Life
Extension Program (SLEP) and periodic replacement of perishable or shelf-life limited medical supplies. The CDML is a diagnostic mobile lab capability that is able to support
pandemic and outbreak response testing. The ERCS is the core capability to patient movement ensuring degradation of patient movement does not occur during transport to the
next level of care. FDPMUs provide deployable Force Health Protection to the Combatant Commanders by rapidly assessing, preventing, and controlling health threats in any
theater of operation. ERSSs are the smallest standard force package of the EHSS family and may be employed afloat, on any vessel, or ashore to provide immediate life and/or
limb saving damage control resuscitation and surgery. It is designed to support disaggregated maritime operations and operate in austere environments.
FDPMUs provide deployable Force Health Protection to the Combatant Commanders by rapidly assessing, preventing, and controlling health threats in any theater of operation.

ERSSs are the smallest standard force package of the EHSS family and may be employed afloat, on any vessel, or ashore to provide immediate life and/or limb saving damage
control resuscitation and surgery. It is designed to support disaggregated maritime operations and operate in austere environments.

FY25 numbers are final. Beginning in FY26, Ship Charter Operations of the MERCY and COMFORT will transition to the 1B1B Line Item while Medical Facilities and
support will transition to 1C1M, Medical Readiness Line Item.

      428                                                                                                                                                  Exhibit OP-5, 2C1H$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 428, 435, $$6df14d0b7bb6d140dadf1e347a106616a093cd81e9cee587e815dbd8705cb280$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3c3l$$, 2027, $$The Navy College Program is the Navy's primary voluntary education financial assistance program. It provides active-duty Sailors with funding for tuition costs for courses taken
in an off-duty status at a regionally, nationally, or professionally accredited college, university, or vocational/technical institution with an approved DOW MOU agreement. The
Voluntary Education Program (VOLED) Program provides military personnel with academic skills, life skills, vocational/technical training and education, and higher education
opportunities. It supports lifelong learning and professional and personal development by allowing service members to pursue a high school diploma, certificate, vocational
certification, or college degree while serving on active duty. Voluntary Education includes Tuition Assistance, Navy College Program for Afloat College Education (NCPACE),
and special graduate education programs for Officers and Enlisted personnel. The VOLED Navy College Director and Deputy Director and Virtual Education Center are in Little
Creek, VA.

Navy College Virtual Education Center (NCVEC) provides a full range of education counseling and education planning services to Sailors virtually via phone, text, email, live-
online-chat, video conferencing and other virtual modalities. It supports lifelong learning and professional and personal development by allowing service members to pursue a high
school diploma, certificate, vocational certification, or college degree while serving on active duty. NCVEC provides information regarding the Joint Service Transcript to active
and retired service members; identifies inconsistent trends in VOLED's processes and procedures specific to counseling, documentation of Sailors' accounts in Navy College
Management Information System (NCMIS), and TA authorizations; processes and authorizes Web TA applications and requests in accordance with higher authority and guidance.

Tuition Assistance (TA) program is the primary method by which active duty and reserve Sailors pursue higher education during off-duty hours. TA pays 100% of tuition and
fees up to the OSW maximum of 18 semester hours (or quarter equivalent) per year with a maximum of 120 semester hours (or quarter equivalent) per career. In addition, Sailors
are required to complete a 2-year minimum time in service requirements before being eligible to use TA. TA also pays 100% of the costs for high school completion courses,
which are not counted against a Sailor's career hour cap.

Navy College Program for Afloat College Education (NCPACE) is a voluntary education program, with separate funding from Tuition Assistance, which is available for
deployable, Type 2 and Type 4 commands and selected remote sites. The Distance Learning (DL) element of NCPACE enrollments utilize the same process as TA and are
subject to the OSW maximum of 12 semester hours (or quarter equivalent) per year with a maximum of 120 semester hours (or quarter equivalent) per career. In addition, Sailors
are required to complete a 2-year minimum active-duty service requirement before being eligible to use NCPACE funding. NCPACE DL offers courses through the Master's
Level Degree. The NCPACE program is made up of entirely distance learning courses administered by way of portable media devices such as CD-ROM or via a one-time course
material download at the start of the program and then a one-time upload of completed assignments at the end of the term. NCPACE contains over 300 independent study/distance
learning courses that are stand-alone and do not require the Internet (except for a one-time download and upload of course materials for some courses) access to complete the
courses from eight (8) academic institutions.

Voluntary Business Operations manages accounting information in Navy College Management Information System (NCMIS) database for financial administration and statistical
analysis to support Navy TA, NCPACE, Graduate Education Voucher (GEV), Advanced Education Voucher (AEV), and Seaman to Admiral (STA21), and Marine Corps and
Coast Guard TA programs. Serves as Debt Collection Manager for the Navy, Marine Corps, and Coast Guard Tuition Assistance programs. Provides invoice processing and
certification supporting to over 900 billing academic institutions averaging approximately 12,000 invoices per fiscal year.

  MANDATORY FUNDING JUSTIFICATION:

  The FY 26 spend plan amount for Weapons Maintenance includes $914 thousand of discretionary and $25,000 thousand of mandatory (reconciliation) for a total of
  $25,914 thousand.
      525                                                                                                                                            Exhibit OP-5, 3C3L$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 525, 533, $$bf98b754753d6b9bcc90015ec286fac286b39ac96c90c15c86243a4242ce12d1$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3c4l$$, 2027, $$The Civilian Education programs are designed to develop and upgrade the professional knowledge and skills of Department of the Navy (DON) civilian employees through
  training, education, and career management at various points in the employees' careers.
  The Financial Management Career Program Office (FMCPO) recruits talented individuals at the entry (Interns and Trainees) and mid-levels (Associates) and coordinates their
  training and diverse work assignments with the homeport commands to become Department of the Navy (DON) financial management (FM) professionals in financial positions at
  Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the United States. The FMCP Program is made up of the following sub-programs: DON Financial Management Associate
  Program (FMAP), the Financial Management Trainee Program (FMTP), and the Financial Management Intern Program (FMIP).

      -     The Department of the Navy (DON) Financial Management Associate Program (FMAP) is a 24-month mid-level career-development program within the Financial
            Management (FM) community. Associates are placed within financial positions at Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the United States. Activities are
            generally headquarters organizations that deal with a myriad of areas, such as design, development, and acquisition of weapon systems; medical support for our Sailors
            and Marines worldwide; operational support of Navy and Marine Corps bases and stations; policy determinations in these areas; and securing the resources—financial and
            human capital—to support these activities.

      -     The Financial Management Trainee Program (FMTP) is a 24-month program of professional development through academic and on-the-job training. Emphasis is placed
            on practical work experience and rotational work assignments as part of the Trainee's professional training. Assignments include all aspects of financial management at
            Navy and Marine Corps commands and academic training in a variety of Navy and Marine Corps financial management operations.

      -     The Financial Management Intern Program (FMIP) is designed to develop and upgrade the professional knowledge and skills of the Department of the Navy (DON)
            civilian employees through training, education, and career management at various points in the employees' careers. The Financial Management Career Program Office
            (FMCPO) recruits talented individuals at the entry (Interns and Trainees) and mid-levels (Associates) and coordinates their training and diverse work assignments with the
            homeport commands to become DON financial management (FM) professionals in financial positions at Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the
            United States.

  The Naval Acquisition Development Program (NADP). The Naval Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP) includes funding for the ASN (RD&A) centrally managed
  Acquisition Developmental Program (ADP). Required by the Defense Acquisition Workforce Improvement Act (DAWIA) (PL 101-510), the ADP provides for centralized
  recruiting, hiring, development and placement of entry level employees in the following back to basics functional areas: Program Management, Contracting, Business Financial
  Management, Business Cost Estimating, Lifecycle Logistics, Engineering and Technical Management, Test and Evaluation. The NADP employs recent college graduates
  (primarily outstanding scholars) developed through highly structured, two, two and a half or three-year program of education, training, rotational assignments, and continuous
  learning activities. Upon graduation, entry-level personnel (formerly called interns) backfill positions throughout the Navy's acquisition organizations due to retirements and other
  attrition.

  The Leadership Development Continuum, encompassing the Commanders Executive Fellows, Journey Level Leadership, and Next Generation is enterprise-wide program and
  establishes a digital platform to design, market, attract, recruit or nominate, manage, access and evaluate the best talent to serve the program. Selected candidates will participate in
  "best in class" learning and development partnerships, alliances and network opportunities. The program will provide candidates developmental curriculum in Strategy, Execution

      534                                                                                                                                                        Exhibit OP-5, 3C4L$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 534, 542, $$8dceb4de3a20c7721205e432de221f9494ba2615d999dc706c8b37f88e021350$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1a9a$$, 2027, $$The Aviation Logistics program provides Navy and Marine Corps aviation programs a budget line item for Contractor Logistics Support (CLS) and Performance Based Logistics
(PBL). CLS is the maintenance performance and/or materiel management functions for a Department of War (DoW) system by a commercial activity. PBL is purchase support as
an integrated performance package designed to optimize system readiness and meet performance goals for a weapon system through long-term support arrangements with clear
lines of authority and responsibility. Below are the current platforms:

The KC-130J – The airframe and Harvest Hawk (HH) variants contractor provides engineering and logistics support services, and Field Service Representatives (FSRs) for the
KC-130J weapon system aircraft. The propulsion support contractor provides propulsion system (engine and propeller) support, which includes all labor and material support for
depot level repair; material for Organizational level scheduled and unscheduled maintenance (repairable and consumable) logistics, engineering, and Field Services
Representatives (FSR) support.

Fat Albert - The propulsion support contractor provides propulsion system (engine and propeller) support, which includes all labor and material support for depot level repair;
material for Organizational level scheduled and unscheduled maintenance (repairable and consumable) logistics, and engineering support.

C/MV-22 – The Joint Performance Based Logistics (PBL) contractor provides services and products supporting the C/MV-22 weapon system aircraft including obsolescence and
configuration management, maintenance planning and supportability analysis, technical data support, in-service engineering and logistics support, training and trainer support, and
peculiar support equipment sustainment. The propulsion support contractor provides engine sustainment on a flight hour basis, Power By the Hour (PBtH), that includes depot
level engine and component repair and O-level material. Services are provided in the form of engine related obsolescence and configuration management, technical data support,
in-service engineering and logistics support, training and trainer support, and sustainment of peculiar support equipment. On-site field service representatives support all
permanent V-22 operating locations.

F-35 – Management Initiative Decision 917 directed Joint Strike Fighter (JSF), one of six pilot programs, to test revised contracting, programming, budgeting, and financing
processes for PBL agreements. The JSF approach is a total PBL government and industry partnership for maintenance and airframe and propulsion systems engineering support
including depot level repairables and consumables, support equipment, Autonomic Logistics Information System (ALIS), simulators and maintenance trainers, aircraft and engine
components, software maintenance, and ferry flight services through separate Performance Based Agreements (PBA). The Flying Hour Program funds fuel and common
consumables for the aircraft.

E-6B – Supports Chairman of Joint Chiefs of Staff (CJCS) and United States Strategic Command (USSTRATCOM), the E-6B mission is to provide survivable, endurable and
reliable Airborne Command, Control, and Communications between the President, Secretary of War and US Strategic and Non-Strategic Forces. Designated with the highest
possible Force Activity Designator (FAD) readiness level set by the Chief of Naval Operations (CNO), the E-6B requires 24/7/365 day a year support, with Commander, Naval Air
Forces (CNAF) Ready For Tasking (RFT) requirement of 12 aircraft out of a fleet of 16 aircraft. The E-6B is the only survivable nuclear hardened weapon system aircraft capable
of performing the CJCS's critical nuclear deterrence through mobile command, control, and communications. There is no back-up platform. The E-6 aircraft is a CLS life-of-type
contractor supported platform. The E-6B Integrated Logistics Support provides logistics support for the 16 aircraft flying ~11,000 flight hours a year in support of national tasking.
The Repair of Repairables (RoR) program provides CLS managed repairable repairs, consumable replenishment including surveyed assets, and support equipment replacement as
well as inventory adjustments needed to support 16 operational E-6B aircraft.

FOD - The Aviation Foreign Object Damage (FOD) Mitigation Program supports aviation foreign object damage prevention for the Navy and Marine Corps.

       95                                                                                                                                                      Exhibit OP-5, 1A9A$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 95, 104, $$689efa38d2d514e9da53d1d154930e2568e6fc051f8515e5adbd4432efcb3a95$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c7c$$, 2027, $$Calibration

  This budget line funds the Navy's essential Calibration System, a network of programs that guarantees the accuracy of every test instrument and shipboard sensor across the
  fleet. From the propulsion plant of a nuclear submarine to the weapon systems on an aircraft carrier, our equipment relies on precise measurements to function safely and
  effectively. This funding ensures that when a Sailor reads a gauge or a technician tests a system, the information is correct—preventing equipment failure, protecting personnel,
  and ensuring mission success. Without proper calibration, the Navy's ships cannot get underway safely, weapons may not fire accurately, and critical repairs could fail. This
  system underpins the technical readiness of the entire force.

    Core Calibration Support; Metrological Engineering and Technical Support (METCAL) & Test and Monitoring Systems (TAMS)
    This funding provides the engineering backbone for the entire Navy calibration enterprise, supporting over 400 laboratories that perform more than 1 million calibrations
    annually.

    Delivering Accuracy to the Fleet: We develop and distribute the thousands of technical procedures used by technicians to calibrate test equipment. This ensures a single,
    verifiable standard of accuracy is maintained everywhere, from a forward-deployed unit to a stateside depot.

    Driving Efficiency and Joint-Service Collaboration: We manage common calibration solutions for all Navy systems commands (SYSCOMs), eliminating redundant efforts
    and saving millions of dollars. By certifying all Navy labs to a common standard, an Air Systems Command lab can service a submarine's equipment, increasing flexibility and
    reducing costs. We also operate the Metrology Data System (MDS), a central database that tracks the performance and calibration status of all test equipment. This data is
    critical for optimizing maintenance schedules and predicting equipment failure before it occurs, maximizing operational availability.

    Shipboard System Integrity (SISCAL)
    This program delivers calibration directly to the installed systems on our warships, focusing on the critical instrumentation that monitors propulsion, electrical power, and
    damage control systems.

    Preventing Catastrophic Failure at Sea: Accurate data from these systems is vital. It allows sailors to take action to prevent a casualty, such as an engine overheating or a loss
    of electrical power. Inaccurate data can lead to false alarms that degrade readiness or, worse, a failure to detect a problem that could result in machinery damage, loss of
    propulsion, or harm to the crew.

    Smart Maintenance that Reduces Sailor Workload: By applying a rigorous analytical process, we have safely eliminated unnecessary calibrations on over one-third (34%) of
    shipboard instruments. This targeted approach significantly reduces maintenance burdens on our sailors, freeing them up for more critical operational duties while still
    guaranteeing the reliability of the ship's systems.

    General Purpose Electronic Test Equipment Engineering (GPETE)
    This funding sustains GPETE used to diagnose and repair every system in the fleet. When a new threat emerges or a system requires an update, we provide the engineering to
    field the necessary test equipment to keep our forces at the cutting edge. This effort is central to managing equipment obsolescence and ensuring our technicians always have
    the tools they need to maintain a fleet-wide test equipment availability of 85%.

      258                                                                                                                                                       Exhibit OP-5, 1C7C$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 258, 266, $$6cf6dbf33731cfc8cf2a5fff00c437c35d45b239a551634e51fe5125cf889cb2$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1d4d$$, 2027, $$The Weapons Maintenance sub-activity group sustains the Navy's essential lifecycle maintenance, engineering, and logistical support for the Navy's entire arsenal of
weapons, unmanned systems, and the critical mission planning software that guides them. From submarine-launched torpedoes to air-launched missiles and the unmanned
vehicles that are reshaping the battlespace, this funding ensures every system is safe, reliable, and ready to perform its mission on demand. The investments in this line
directly translate to a more capable, more lethal, and more ready Fleet by delivering tangible outcomes, from overhauling more than 25 CIWS gun systems to
executing maintenance on 120 MK 48 heavyweight torpedoes annually.

Weapons & Ordnance Sustainment — Guaranteeing the Kinetic Edge
Directly funds the readiness of the Navy's kinetic firepower. It ensures that every missile, torpedo, gun, and shell is safe, reliable, and ready to perform as designed, from
the moment it is loaded until it strikes its target. This funding is not just about repair; it is about managing the end-to-end lifecycle of our ordnance to guarantee the
lethality and credibility of our surface, subsurface, and air forces.

Air-Launched & Surface-Launched Missiles: This funding sustains the combat-readiness of our entire missile inventory. In FY27, this includes the All-Up-Round (AUR)
recertification of 150 STANDARD Missiles (SM-2/SM-6), the depot repair of 100 Evolved Sea Sparrow Missile (ESSM) sections, and the overhaul of 80 Rolling
Airframe Missile (RAM) canisters. These efforts ensure our naval aviators and surface warships have a reliable and effective weapon for every mission, from air-to-air
combat to fleet air defense.

Subsurface Weapons & Combat Systems: We fund the essential depot maintenance and engineering for the Navy's premier undersea weapons, including the MK 48
Heavyweight and MK 54 Lightweight Torpedoes. This work, which includes planned maintenance on over 120 torpedoes annually, is critical to ensuring our submarine
force has a guaranteed inventory of reliable weapons to dominate the undersea domain. We also provide continuous fleet support and repair for combat systems on all
submarine classes, ensuring they can safely and effectively employ these weapons.

Strike Weapons & Gun Systems: This funding provides for the lifecycle maintenance of our premier strike weapon, the Tomahawk missile, by supporting and
certifying 19 worldwide Intermediate Maintenance Activities (IMAs). It also sustains shipboard gun systems that are a primary means of offense and defense, funding the
overhaul of 25 Phalanx Close-In Weapon Systems (CIWS) to the latest Block 1B configuration and maintaining our major caliber guns like the MK 45.

Direct Fleet Engineering Support: This pillar funds the subject matter expertise that directly supports our sailors. Our engineering teams provide rapid-response technical
assistance for over 300 emergent Fleet Casualty Reports (CASREPs) annually, deliver critical hands-on training to aviation ordnance technicians, and develop solutions to
emerging reliability and safety issues. This support reduces costs by enabling repairs at the lowest possible level and directly contributes to maximizing system uptime
and fleet readiness.

C4ISR & Mission Planning — Sustaining Decision Advantage
This funding sustains the digital backbone that enables our warfighters to plan, execute, and dominate in complex, contested environments. This is the capability that turns
data into decisions and actions. These systems provide commanders with a clear picture of the battlespace, give pilots the tools to execute precision strikes, and protect our
vital networks from adversary intrusion.

Mission Planning & Control Systems: This funding is vital for the software that allows our forces to plan and execute complex missions. It sustains systems like the Naval
Mission Planning System (NavMPS) and Tomahawk's Theater Mission Planning Center (TMPC) by funding the resolution of more than 500 Software Trouble Reports
      310                                                                                                                                                    Exhibit OP-5, 1D4D$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 310, 331, $$ef6d5cdd0b7b7df54284aa946112906ae7a583c7b2553aa9ed34cf0bc61898be$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c5c$$, 2027, $$Funding within this activity group supports the performance of the Naval Meteorology and Oceanographic mission functions worldwide and provides a wide array of essential
operational meteorological and oceanographic products and services to operating forces afloat and ashore. These services include collecting and processing environmental data
using resources such as oceanographic ships, aircraft, satellites, and computing systems. These products and services enhance the performance of active and passive sensor and
weapon systems; optimize the effectiveness of the sea control mission for mine counter-measures; and identify the environmental effects that influence the performance of fixed
and mobile warfare systems and tactics. Hydrographic data from near shore areas supports the production of coastal, combat, approach, harbor and special purpose nautical charts
used to address littoral warfare requirements. General and tailored oceanographic, acoustic and meteorological forecasts provided daily to fleet commanders and individual
operating units from the Meteorology and Oceanography Command's numerical modeling and forecasting centers and from forecasting support activities located worldwide.
Funding also supports the U.S. Naval Observatory's mission to provide Precise Time and Time Interval (PTTI), Astrometry, Astrometry (Celestial Reference Frame CRF), and
Earth Orientation products to DOW and other government agencies. As DOW's designated PTTI manager, the Naval Observatory maintains the Master Clock, and provides
essential PTTI information to space surveillance, communications, and navigation systems, including the Navigation Satellite Timing & Ranging (NAVSTAR) Global Positioning
System (GPS). Astrometry and Earth Orientation products provide vital support for various strategic and tactical programs including precise targeting and positioning of ballistic
missiles, stellar navigation, and intelligence collection and mapping using satellites.

Oceanographic Ship Operations: All days at sea per year (transit, survey, rescue mission, etc.) as well as all days in port per year (VRA, diplomatic, resupply, etc.) and
Geotechnical analysis support and ISS-60 life cycle support systems.

Oceanographic Collections and Deployments: Meteorological and Oceanographic Support Systems such as Satellite Support and Oceanographic Models; Maritime Homeland
Defense Systems; Exercises; Unmanned Underwater Vehicle (UUV) Deployments; Ocean Products; Acoustic Products; Mine Warfare (MIW) Products; Builder Products; Target
Acquisition Weapon Software (TAWS) Products and METOC Support Products.

Weather & Fleet Safety (Deployable Fleet Support): All facets of weather support to at-sea and shore based naval forces, operations and facilities. This entails aviation weather
forecasting products and services for naval aviation, maritime and tropical weather forecasting and warnings, naval resource protection recommendations and operational warfare
support to Carrier Strike Groups (CSGs) and Amphibious Ready Groups (ARGs).

Operational Environmental Modeling: Supports oceanographic environmental characterization worldwide and provides an array of essential operational oceanographic products
and services to operating forces afloat and ashore and supports the worldwide production and delivery of operational meteorological products and services to Navy/DOW assets
afloat and ashore.

Operational Command, Interagency Liaison and Ed & Training: Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW) and Mine Information Warfare (MIW) direct Fleet support such as
deploying ASW and MIW teams and utilizes reach-back cells. Enables capabilities acoustic models and databases, and collection of oceanographic and geophysical data as
required by COCOM Components. Supports CNO's Undersea Dominance initiatives.

Operational Meteorology and Oceanography: Supports the performance of Naval Meteorological and Oceanographic mission functions worldwide as well as Intelligence
Preparation of the Operational Environment (IPOE) for Information Warfare (associated warfare areas and operations), Safety of Navigation (surface and submarine), Safety of
Flight, and Resource Protection. It also provides funding for In-Service Engineering Agent (ISEA) and Software Support Activity (SSA) efforts including engineering and logistics
support for all Navy and Marine Corps meteorological equipment. Funding will enable the timely introduction and support of various meteorological and oceanographic equipment
such as Naval Integrated Tactical Environmental System Next Generation (NITES-Next), Marine Corps Meteorological Mobile Facility Replacement Next Generation
       228                                                                                                                                                    Exhibit OP-5, 1C5C$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 228, 240, $$0dd67ee722346d4c39221afb9c4fe54466aa8dff3c1a8e9e3dbb5819f03d1b7c$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3b1k$$, 2026, $$Specialized Skill Training resources are used to maintain a trained force of personnel capable of manning and supporting surface, sub-surface, aviation operating forces and their
installed complex weapons systems. Enlisted personnel receive broad career-field and Naval Enlisted Classification (NEC) ratings upon completion of initial and advanced training
programs in areas such as intelligence, cryptologic signals and nuclear power operation. Costs for Specialized Skill Training include civilian labor, travel, supplies, material,
contractor training and costs. Provides for contracted instructor effort to augment military instructors to support training loads, and for contractor maintenance in support of
training programs.
Boat Overhaul. Supports the phased maintenance and life cycle replacement requirements of all training support watercraft, including the maintenance and upkeep of Yard Diving
Tenders (YDT) and small boats.
Counter Drug. Supports the Drug Demand Reduction (DDR) and Supply Reduction program. DDR costs include purchase of supplies required for collection of specimens for
urinalysis and programs that discourage drug use. Supply Reduction provides training to international students primary by Mobile Training Teams (MTTs) in countries including
Mexico and Colombia.
Cryptic Skill Program Training. Cyber, Information Warfare (IW) and Cryptologic and Sigint skill training, conducted under the oversight and guidance of the National Security
Agency and Central Security Service (NSA/CSS, and Commander, Navy Cyber Forces (NCF) supports strategic national and fleet tactical warfighting requirements by responding
to target developments and the rapidly evolving global signals environment.
Environmental Training. The Civil Engineer Corps Officer School (CECOS) Environmental Division is the Executive Agent for Navy environmental education. The civilians in
this division are subject matter experts that develop, deliver, and maintain environmental education and training to the Navy, worldwide. Courses directly support the OPNAV N45
mission to maintain Navy operations in a regulatory compliant manner, as well as, maintaining stewardship of the environment. This program also supports other Department of
Defense services and partnering federal and state regulatory agencies.
General Specialized Skill Program Training. Maintains a trained force of personnel capable of manning and supporting surface, sub-surface, and aviation operating forces and their
installed complex weapon systems. Navy Specialized Skill Training is conducted at eleven Learning Centers and their training sites, three direct report schools; and three Training
Support Centers located throughout the country. Specialized Skill Training is also obtained through contractual services. Funding for the Specialized Skill Program Training
finances the cost of civilian labor, travel, supplies and materials consumed in conducting training courses, contractor training, and general administrative expenses. Funding is also
provided for contracting instructor's effort to augment military instructors to support training loads, and funds are provided for contractor maintenance in support of training
programs.
          Fuel. Provides commercial fuel and Working Capital Fund (WCF) fuel purchases through the Defense Fuel Supply Center (DFSC).
Homeland Defense. Training of security and protective forces used to safeguard assets, personnel, information and conduct expeditionary warfare and security force mission
worldwide. Includes, but is not limited to, dedicated response teams, human intelligence, communications intelligence, electronic intelligence, security forces, locksmiths, military
working dog handlers, and antiterrorism awareness program instruction. Supports training for performing safe recovery, evaluation and disposal of surface and underwater
explosive ordnance and nuclear weapons.
Naval Aviation Schools Command (NASC). The Naval Aviation Schools Command delivers foundational aviator, aircrew, and survival training for enlisted and officer personnel
to achieve fleet requirements in support of Naval aviation warfighting. NASC manages the Naval Introductory Flight Evaluation (NIFE) program which provides students with
fundamental aviation knowledge, introduces military procedural-based training and performance standards, provides aeronautical adaptability screening, decreases attrition later in
the training pipelines, and improves overall student performance during Primary flight training.
Navy Intelligence Foreign Language Program (NIFLP). Provides Navy personnel initial, acquisition-level education language courses at the Defense Language Institute Foreign
Language Center (DLIFLC) Monterey, California, DLIFLC Washington, District of Columbia and various other locations. Provides recurrent intermediate and advanced training
to sustain and enhance global language skills among Navy language analysts (Cryptologic Technicians Interpretive rating [CTI]). Provides for the technical training of CTIs
preparing for national/joint collection and analysis operations.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 510, 524, $$b353486c42a0da01c5eeab9cedd56b8ce31dfb24a8c7537f19486bff142f7af7$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3b3k$$, 2026, $$Professional Development Education prepares career officers for more demanding assignments, particularly command and staff positions. It is concerned with broad professional
goals in subjects such as military science, engineering, and management.

The Naval War College (NWC) includes the Department's senior and intermediate colleges and is organized into three academic departments: Strategy and Policy, National
Security and Decision Making and Joint Military Operations. In addition, NWC houses the Center for War-gaming and the Strategic Studies Group, and provides the resident
education for foreign naval officers. The distance education program closely parallels the resident curriculum and is offered via various methodologies--Fleet Seminars, Web-
Enabled courses and CD-ROMs.

Navy Professional Military Education (NPME) is an integral component of the Professional Military Education (PME) continuum. NPME supports fleet requirements for
fundamental, intermediate and professional knowledge for all Sailors, officer and enlisted, through the following core competencies: Navy/military studies, professionalism, and
national and global security. NPME courses assist in growth and career-long development from accession through the executive levels of Navy service.

The Naval Postgraduate School (NPS) is an accredited institution offering graduate degree programs with specific defense emphasis, particularly in science, engineering and
technical areas. It also maintains a graduate level research program that responds to the emerging needs of the Navy.

The United States Naval Community College (USNCC) was established by the Secretary of the Navy in 2019 to increase naval educational opportunities for over 450,000 active-
duty Sailors and Marines. USNCC is establishing academic programs in technical and non-technical fields, which are relevant to the current and future needs of the Navy and
Marine Corps, including in designated fields of national and economic importance such as cybersecurity, artificial intelligence, machine learning, data science, and software
engineering. Programs would also incorporate critical 21st Century skills through instruction in the fields of the liberal arts and sciences. USNCC is addressing student success and
learning outcomes by developing remedial, developmental, or continuing education programs and support and advisement services for individuals pursuing such programs and
continuous monitoring of the progress of USNCC students. USNCC is also pursuing academic accreditation for its degree programs.

Resources predominantly support the expansion of the number of enrolled students as well as an increase in course offerings as USNCC progresses towards full operational
capability by 2026. As an accredited education institute, USNCC will be responsible for all academic related support and execution infrastructure. USNCC is operating through a
consortium model with the top academic programs in the country, which specialize in professional concentration and general education programs that meet the needs of the naval
services. The USNCC-led consortium will expand to up to twenty partner institutions by the end of FY 2028. The USNCC is responsible for designing world-class programs based
on the feedback provided by the naval operating forces.

Naval Education Training Command (NETC)/Naval Education and Training Professional Development Center (NETPDC) supports the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
Defense College is a Joint North Atlantic Treaty Organization effort staffed by the various military services of the participating countries. Funding for this program provides for
student travel and per diem required by the curriculum and administrative costs such as official telephone calls and mail delivery for assigned U.S. students.

         The Officer Short Courses provides payment for tuition and travel for Officers in the Federal Executive Fellowship, Foreign War College, and Executive Fellowship
         programs.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 525, 538, $$0513f6090de8f2f5afd69a59860552ff6dc8a83f2fa9b2974c00d42734350771$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3b4k$$, 2026, $$Training Support encompasses various programs that push to revolutionize the way the Navy attracts, retains, and trains Sailors. These programs provide Navy-wide support to
training headquarters, activities and equipment. These programs include:

 Electronic Classrooms Training Delivery Services (TDS) is NETC's training services infrastructure providing foundational delivery of RRL modernized training content to
 student and instructors. It provides classified/unclassified internet and base-level connectivity across 60+ CONUS/OCONUS locations supporting 2,500+ classrooms and
 23,000+ workstations. TDS provides the ECR IT infrastructure and architecture required for delivery, management, and sustainment of RRL content fielding and the entire NETC
 training enterprise.

 Claimant Support provides support for the Naval Education and Training Command (NETC) Human Resources Office (HRO), NETC Support Staff, the Supply Chain and
 Logistics Branch located in Millington Tennessee, and NETC Headquarters (HQ) administrative services contract. This includes funding for contract personnel (site supervisor,
 mail clerk, quarterdeck receptionist, and admin services such as the travel clerk).
 Authoring Instructional Materials (AIM) capabilities that provide highly efficient design, development, surveillance, maintenance and production of training/educational materials
 is being migrated to the Curriculum Data System (CDS) within the Transformation Learning Stack. These capabilities automate instructor led curriculum development processes
 used in support of Navy Training. It provides automated conformance to NAVEDTRA standards and learning requirements to work definitions based on NETC Job Duty Task
 Analysis (JDTA) standards per NETCINST 1510.4.

 Command and Administration support headquarters personnel and associated operating cost for Naval Education and Training Command (NETC) at Pensacola, FL.

 Naval Education and Training Professional Development Center (NETPDC) provides the hosting for delivery of Sailor 2025/RRL modernized learning content in the classified
 environment. Supported functions: delivery of classified learning content, instructional content development, and advancement exams for classified ratings. SIPR DC provides
 support for NETC's portfolio of IT systems, classified (SIPR/NNPI) training environment and users. Support includes classified infrastructure, physical environment, information
 assurance security controls, servers and storage.

 Enterprise Services (ES), a collection of Information Technology capabilities that provide critical services/functions (i.e., Active Directory, Security Controls, Data Transfer,
 Enterprise Service Bus, etc.) for NETC systems that currently reside in the Naval Enterprise Data Center (NEDC) in New Orleans (NOLA) with Disaster Recovery/COOP
 alternate hosting site in Kansas City (KC). NETC ES is included in Cloud migration service provider requirements, which are currently being explored. Until all NETC PORs
 have Transformed, NETC ES is required to provide critical functions for POR operations, user access, and database functionality.

 Central Design Activity (CDA) Management the NETC CIO support staff is responsible for all roles and responsibilities assigned to traditional CIO/Portfolio Management
 support tasks. This includes CIO strategic support, IT system support, Project Management/Agile, IT capital planning, and budgeting. The support staff is responsible for NETC
 CIO compliance with DoD/DoN policies, DADMS/DITPR-DON compliance, development and maintenance of the NETC Portfolio of Applications, and associated investment
 and budgetary analysis.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 539, 555, $$09185aae363f667226bb459246f5072966b8a5feb6a4ab1429746061591b3b11$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_3c4l$$, 2026, $$The Civilian Education programs are designed to develop and upgrade the professional knowledge and skills for Department of the Navy (DON) civilian employees through training,
  education, and career management at various points in the employees' careers.
   The Financial Management Career Program Office (FMCPO) recruits talented individuals at the entry (Interns and Trainees) and mid-levels (Associates) and coordinates their
   training and diverse work assignments with the homeport commands to become Department of the Navy (DON) financial management (FM) professionals in financial positions at
   Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the United States. The FMCP Program is made up of the following sub-programs: DON Financial Management Associate
   Program (FMAP), the Financial Management Trainee Program (FMTP), and the Financial Management Intern Program (FMIP).

         The Department of the Navy (DON) Financial Management Associate Program (FMAP) is a 24 month mid-level career-development program within the financial
         management (FM) community. Associates are placed within financial positions at Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the United States. Activities are
         generally headquarters organizations that deal with a myriad of areas, such as: design, development, and acquisition of weapon systems; medical support for our Sailors and
         Marines worldwide; operational support of Navy and Marine Corps bases and stations; policy determinations in these areas; and securing the resources—financial and human
         capital—to support these activities.

         The Financial Management Trainee Program (FMTP) is a 24-month program of professional development through academic and on-the-job training. Emphasis is placed on
         practical work experience and rotational work assignments as part of the Trainee's professional training. Assignments include all aspects of financial management at Navy
         and Marine Corps commands and academic training in a variety of Navy and Marine Corps financial management operations.

         The Financial Management Intern Program (FMIP) is designed to develop and upgrade the professional knowledge and skills of Department of the Navy (DON) civilian
         employees through training, education, and career management at various points in the employees' careers. The Financial Management Career Program Office (FMCPO)
         recruits talented individuals at the entry (Interns and Trainees) and mid-levels (Associates) and coordinates their training and diverse work assignments with the homeport
         commands to become DON financial management (FM) professionals in financial positions at Navy and Marine Corps Commands located throughout the United States.

  The Naval Acquisition Development Program (NADP). The Naval Acquisition Developmental Program (NADP) includes funding for the ASN (RD&A) centrally managed
  Acquisition Developmental Program (ADP). Required by the Defense Acquisition Workforce Improvement Act (DAWIA) (PL 101-510), the ADP provides for centralized
  recruiting, hiring, development and placement of entry level employees in the following back to basics functional areas: Program Management, Contracting, Business Financial
  Management, Business Cost Estimating, Lifecycle Logistics, Engineering and Technical Management, Test and Evaluation. The NADP employs recent college graduates (primarily
  outstanding scholars) developed through highly structured, two, two and a half or three-year program of education, training, rotational assignments, and continuous learning
  activities. Upon graduation, entry level personnel (formerly called interns) backfill positions throughout the Navy's acquisition organizations due to retirements and other attrition.

  The Leadership Development Continuum, encompassing the Commanders Executive Fellows, Journey Level Leadership, and Next Generation is an enterprise-wide program and
  establishes a digital platform to design, market, attract, recruit or nominate, manage, access and evaluate the best talent to serve the program. Selected candidates will participate in a
  "best in class" learning and development partnerships, alliances and network opportunities. Program will provide candidates developmental curriculum in Strategy, Execution and
  Finance; NAVSEA and industry courses led by Senior Leadership covering ethics, NAVSEA competencies, industrial operations, history, DON & DOD acquisition and
  communications; mentoring and coaching and rotational assignments.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 573, 580, $$61a8f3d2014960152b1f7eb6991ea862e6b0acfd5be9db58a17503a33f4fb873$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1a9a$$, 2026, $$The Aviation Logistics program provides Navy and Marine Corps aviation programs a budget line item for Contractor Logistics Support (CLS) and Performance Based Logistics
(PBL). CLS is the maintenance performance and/or materiel management functions for a DoD system by a commercial activity. PBL is purchase support as an integrated
performance package designed to optimize system readiness and meet performance goals for a weapon system through long-term support arrangements with clear lines of authority
and responsibility. Below are the current platforms:

The KC-130J – The airframe and Harvest Hawk (HH) variants contractor provides engineering and logistics support services, and Field Service Representatives (FSRs) for the
KC-130J weapon system aircraft. The propulsion support contractor provides propulsion system (engine and propeller) support, which includes all labor and material support for
depot level repair; material for Organizational level scheduled and unscheduled maintenance (repairable and consumable) logistics, engineering, and Field Services
Representatives (FSR) support.

Fat Albert - The propulsion support contractor provides propulsion system (engine and propeller) support, which includes all labor and material support for depot level repair;
material for Organizational level scheduled and unscheduled maintenance (repairable and consumable) logistics, and engineering support.

C/MV-22 – The Joint Performance Based Logistics (PBL) contractor provides services and products supporting the C/MV-22 weapon system aircraft including obsolescence and
configuration management, sustainment of maintenance planning and supportability analysis, technical data support, in-service engineering and logistics support, training and
trainer support, and peculiar support equipment sustainment. The propulsion support contractor provides engine sustainment on a flight hour basis, Power By the Hour (PBtH),
that includes depot level engine and component repair and O-level material. Services are provided in the form of engine related obsolescence and configuration management,
technical data support, in-service engineering and logistics support, training and trainer support, and sustainment of peculiar support equipment. On-site field service
representatives support all permanent V-22 operating locations.

F-35 – Management Initiative Decision 917 directed Joint Strike Fighter (JSF), one of six pilot programs, to test revised contracting, programming, budgeting, and financing
processes for PBL agreements. The JSF approach is a total PBL government and industry partnership for maintenance and airframe and propulsion systems engineering support
including depot level repairables and consumables, support equipment, Autonomic Logistics Information System (ALIS), simulators and maintenance trainers, aircraft and engine
components, software maintenance, and ferry flight services through separate Performance Based Agreements (PBA). The Flying Hour Program funds fuel and common
consumables for the aircraft.

E-6B – Supports Chairman of Joint Chiefs of Staff (CJCS) and United States Strategic Command (USSTRATCOM), the E-6B mission is to provide survivable, endurable and
reliable Airborne Command, Control, and Communications between the President, Secretary of Defense and US Strategic and Non-Strategic Forces. Designated with the highest
possible Force Activity Designator (FAD) readiness level set by the Chief of Naval Operations (CNO), the E-6B requires 24/7/365 day a year support, with Commander, Naval Air
Forces (CNAF) stated Ready For Tasking (RFT) requirement of 12 aircraft out of a fleet of 16 aircraft. The E-6B is the only survivable nuclear hardened weapon system aircraft
capable of performing the CJCS's critical nuclear deterrence through mobile command, control, and communications. There is no back-up platform. The E-6 aircraft is a CLS life-
of-type contractor supported platform. The E-6B Integrated Logistics Support provides logistics support for the 16 aircraft flying ~11,000 flight hours a year in support of national
tasking. In FY24, one trainer aircraft (TE-6B) will be introduced, flying ~600 flight hours a year to maintain pilot proficiency. This trainer will alleviate the structural stress of
repeated touch and go landing cycles on the E-6B airframe. The Repair of Repairables (RoR) program provides CLS managed repairable repairs, consumable replenishment
including surveyed assets, and support equipment replacement as well as inventory adjustments needed to support 16 operational E-6B aircraft and one trainer (TE-6B).

FOD - The Aviation Foreign Object Damage (FOD) Mitigation Program supports aviation foreign object damage prevention for the Navy and Marine Corps.
In FY25, 1A4A budget exhibits for the Aviation Mobile Facilities program operations financed is consolidated and reflected in the 1A9A
budget exhibits.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 116, 125, $$04e2208144cf45c8b8399a9360c060dc7477761d8b78d98dabc76c4968cac2c2$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_reserve_4a4m$$, 2026, $$This sub-activity group funds maintenance and support for the following military manpower and personnel management systems: Navy Reserve Order Writing System (NROWS),
Reserve Headquarters Support (RHS) System, Reserve Integrated Management System (RIMS) Financial Management (FM), and Inactive Manpower and Personnel Management
Information System (IMAPMIS). Navy Personnel and Pay (NP2) is one of the cornerstones of the Navy/N1 Transformation strategy formerly known as Navy Standard Integrated
Personnel System (NSIPS). NP2 includes Navy Personnel and Pay sustainment and the collapse of Legacy Manpower Systems' functionality. NP2 is the Human Resources (HR)
component of Navy's Transformation Roadmap specifically focused on maximizing human capital and improving fleet readiness by ensuring the right skills are in the right place at
the right time. Also funded are all functions related to Reserve personnel management performed by the Navy Reserve Personnel Management Department (PERS-9).

Reserve Integrated Management System (RIMS): Reserve Integrated Management System (RIMS) Financial Management (FM) is a mission critical Financial Management
application created to manage those funds appropriated by Congress to the Navy Reserves. The system allows the entry and processing of two primary transactions reservations
and adjustments. The RIMS (FM) system handles information that is necessary for the conduct of day-to-day businesses, but does not materially affect support to deployed or
contingency forces in the short term.

Naval Information Warfare Center (NIWC) Atlantic IT Center - New Orleans (RES): The Naval Information Warfare Center (NIWC) Atlantic, New Orleans is located in
the Research and Technology Park of the University of New Orleans. The manpower and personnel systems supported by NIWC New Orleans are required by all Navy active
duty, reserve, and retired personnel. Systems are deployed in every state at Navy Recruiting Centers, Personnel Support Detachments, and Navy Operational Support Centers.
NIWC Atlantic provides direct operations and maintenance support to Navy Reserve business systems, and site overhead/indirect operational support including, but not limited to
travel, training, & supplies.

Navy Reserve Order Writing System (NROWS): Navy Reserve Order Writing System (NROWS) is a consolidated information system that combines all Commander, Naval
Reserve Force (CNRF) order-writing functions. NROWS is a single, enterprise-wide application for putting a Reservist on Annual Training (AT), Active Duty Training (ADT),
and Inactive Duty Training Travel (IDTT) orders. It provides users and managers with information on total force readiness and availability for operational planning. The objective
of NROWS is to perform many of the data impact edits as early in the order writing process as possible. Meeting this objective reduces the number of applications and order
validations currently being performed manually and greatly decreases the application error rate.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMNR_Book.pdf$$, 121, 128, $$19e4a4a6d7c6d0aad8ec4ad0db488ecbc620e3b37717c5f399665774662bcb00$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1a5a$$, 2026, $$A. Airframe Rework: This program provides Fleet aircraft inspection, rework and emergent repairs. Through periodic depot level maintenance activities, aircraft major structures
and airframe systems are maintained in a safe flyable condition. Depot maintenance is currently being performed under the Integrated Maintenance Concept (IMC), Phase Depot
Maintenance (PDM) and other scheduled and unscheduled depot maintenance programs. The IMC concept uses Planned Maintenance Intervals (PMI), performing depot
maintenance, with smaller work packages, reducing out of service time. The program's goal is to improve readiness and availability while reducing operating and support costs.
Currently, the AV-8B, C-130, C-2, E-2, EA-18G, FA-18, H-1, H-53, H-60, MV-22, and P-3 and P-8 are supported under IMC. The PDM concept is used with the E-6B, F-16 and
Executive Helicopter aircraft. MQ-4, MQ-8, other cargo, test pilot and trainer aircraft programs are supported under other scheduled rework programs.

B. Engine Rework: The engine rework program accomplishes aircraft engine, engine modules, gearboxes and torque meters repair and overall. The program objective is to return
depot-repairable engines to ready-for-issue (RFI) status to support Fleet aircraft and Fleet engine pool requirements. Under the Reliability Centered Maintenance (RCM) Program
engines are repaired at the lowest level of maintenance possible. Engines beyond the intermediate maintenance activities repair capability are scheduled for depot induction.
Engine field team is included in this budget submission to provide on-site depot level maintenance on an as-needed basis.

C. Components: The component repair program supports depot level aircraft mission systems and equipment component repair under programs and projects that do not have a
Material Support Date (MSD) established. Additionally, Contractor Logistics Support (CLS) support is provided for closed-loop weapon systems and equipment for Presidential
Helicopter and trainer aircraft propeller repair that will be commercially supported for its life cycle.

D. Depot Readiness Initiative – AVDLR: The Depot Readiness Initiative (DRI) utilizes depot capacity (i.e. skilled depot level artisans) to accomplish select Organizational level
(O-level) tasks (repairs, inspections, technical directive incorporation, etc.) into Phased Depot Maintenance (PDM) and Planned Maintenance Interval (PMI) events. This initiative
expedites the delivery of a Mission Capable (MC) aircraft to the squadron following a depot event. O-level DRI maintenance events may include special inspections, phase/hourly
inspections, Technical Directives (TDs), ordering the non-RFI component replacements and unscheduled maintenance (over and aboves.)

E. Calibration: The Calibration program is the sole method utilized to sustain required in-service measurement of Test, Measurement and Diagnostic Equipment (TMDE) and
Aviation Support Equipment (SE) accuracy. This equipment is used to test, repair, and maintain aircraft, Aviation Weapon Systems, and other measurement-based performance
verifications. This program establishes and maintains Calibration Laboratory Reference Standards (CALSTDs) and supporting technical products/services to ensure aviation
measurement parameters are traceable and accurate to US National standards held at the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST). Program funds sustain aviation 'I'
and 'D' level cal lab capability, and 'D' level man-hours for asset cal beyond Fleet capability. Calibration is an on-cycle maintenance action for all quantitative equipment, which
must be removed from service if left un-calibrated.

F. Ground Support Equipment Rework: The SE Rework Program provides the management, facilities, equipment, material, and manpower to perform Depot Level
Maintenance for Aviation Support Equipment.

G. Aviation Mobile Facilities: The Aviation Mobile Facilities program supports Aviation Mobile Facility configurations for the Navy and Marine Corps.

A Mobile Facility (MF) is a tactical shelter that meets structural and dimensional requirements of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the American National
Standards Institute (ANSI), and the American Society for Testing and Material (ASTM). Designed for a 20-year service life. MFs are heated and cooled by Environmental Control
Units. All configuration of units is completed at Maintenance Depot Marine Core Base in Albany, Georgia. Occasional MF and equipment rework is performed at Blount Island
Command for the USMC Maritime Prepositioning Ships (MPS) program.$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY26/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 98, 107, $$d32f06bdf12d5c7131fcc967b035060bb526e82d0730714691a4485b12eca1e6$$, $$2026-05-10T00:20:58.246153+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_4b3n$$, 2027, $$Naval Supply Systems Command (NAVSUP): Provides logistical and quality of life support to sailors around the world. The Enterprise executes the mission along
        several business lines: Quality of Life, Logistics Operations, Global Logistics, Supply Program, Business Systems and Material Handling Equipment. Across these
        business lines are distinct products and services that enable NAVSUP to support Navy requirements. These products and services play a key role in maintaining
        warfighter readiness and improving the quality of life for Sailors and their families.

        Sailor and Family Care

        NEXCOM: Provides sailors and their families quality goods and services at retail locations. Additional services include, Ship Stores that support sailors while afloat,
        NEXMARTs (small grocery stores in remote locations), and Navy Lodges.

        Clothing Uniform Management: Provides life-cycle management and in-service engineering activity functions for Navy uniforms and for general-purpose organizational
        clothing.

        Household Goods Services: Supports operations and services relating to moving Sailors, their families and household goods worldwide.

        Postal Services: Provides operations and services of post office functions aboard all USS and USNS ships, and ashore facilities worldwide.

        Navy Cash: Gives sailors access to their money while deployed. Responsible for the disbursing policy, guidance, field examination group, Navy Cash® Automated Teller
        Machines (ATMs-at-sea) and the fleet assistance team.

        Food Service: The Navy Food Service Program provides operational and financial policy guidance designed to improve the quality of life for Sailors by ensuring our
        Navy general messes, ashore and afloat, efficiently and economically deliver high-quality nutritious foods that exceed customer expectations.

        Global Logistics Support

        NAVSUP Fleet Logistics Centers (FLCs) are strategically located throughout the United States and overseas which provide direct support to the warfighter.

        1.       NAVSUP FLC Bahrain
        2.       NAVSUP FLC Jacksonville
        3.       NAVSUP FLC Norfolk
        4.       NAVUSP FLC Pearl Harbor
        5.       NAVSUP FLC Puget Sound
        6.       NAVSUP FLC San Diego
        7.       NAVSUP FLC Sigonella
        8.       NAVSUP FLC Yokosuka
      645                                                                                                                                                    Exhibit OP-5, 4B3N$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 645, 659, $$f32c0496e0d25c516764b481bca291587db38c7522a9b0699444eae1f80fe34f$$, $$2026-05-10T00:54:52.462683+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_bsit$$, 2027, $$Programs funded in the Enterprise Information Technology budget line item provide foundational support for the Department of the Navy (DON) Information Superiority Vision.
The DON must securely deliver the right information to the right Sailor or Marine at the right time to defeat high-paced and evolving threats. As we adopt a model that allows us to
modernize, innovate, and defend our platform, we unlock this future. The network itself becomes a warfighting platform.

This budget continues to support key focus areas of Naval Cloud Productivity and Data Availability. The DON continues to shift enterprise collaboration and productivity tools
and services to a cloud-based Microsoft 365 solution with improved security. The DON works to provide access to trustworthy and understandable data that supports mission-
centered analytics

This budget also continues efforts to consolidate DON financial systems and enhance cybersecurity controls to improve data integrity. A modern systems environment replaces
components and reduces a need for manual intervention. An agile disparate architecture supporting an efficient network of applications, services, suppliers, and capabilities will
allow DON to innovate, pivot rapidly and automate business processes. Funding supports ongoing efforts to consolidate into two DoN General Ledgers and decommission legacy
feeder systems to streamline the DON's systems environment and increase compliance with Federal Information Technology standards, including the Federal Information System
Controls Audit Manual and Federal Financial Management Improvement Act.

This subactivity groups critical funded Information Technology programs in the following categories:

Enterprise Network Architecture
Next Generation Enterprise Network (NGEN)
Navy Commercial Cloud Services (NCCS)
Oracle Enterprise Software
Navy Enterprise Service Desk (NESD)
Program Executive Office for Digital and Enterprise Services (PEO DES)
Data Center Consolidation and Navy Cloud Migration
Outside the continental United States (OCONUS) Navy Enterprise Network (ONE-Net) programs

Data Analytics and Management Decision Support Tools
Navy JUPITER
Force Level Integration (FLINT)
DOW IT Portfolio Repository (DITPR)-DoN
DON Application and Database Management System (DADMS)
Navy Medical Information Technology
Visibility & Management of Operation & Support Costs (VAMOSC)
Information Technology Services (NAV-ITAS)

Financial Management and Defense Business Systems
Navy Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP)
    - Accounting Systems:
            o Standard Accounting, Budgeting, and Reporting System (SABRS)
       341                                                                                                                                                   Exhibit OP-5, BSIT$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 341, 365, $$4b77431ce9d3d8d7258ed3c03de7835540aa709f1e6686da3e07171d59a81499$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_2b2g$$, 2027, $$Ship Inactivations
This subactivity supports Non-nuclear/Conventional Inactive Ship Maintenance Facility Support, Non-nuclear/Conventional Surface Ship Inactivation, Nuclear Surface Ship
Inactivation, and Nuclear Submarine Inactivation.

Non-nuclear/Conventional Inactive Ship Maintenance Facility Support
Provides for the operation of three Government-Owned-Contractor-Operated (GOCO) Inactive Ship On-Site Maintenance Offices (ISMO) at Bremerton, WA, Pearl Harbor, HI,
and Philadelphia, PA. Operations include inactivation, storage, maintenance, and preparation of ships for disposal.

Non-nuclear/Conventional Surface Ship Inactivation
Inactivation of conventionally powered ships includes depot level inactivation work to layup a ship. The composition and disposition of inactive ships is reviewed annually to
determine the number of ships held for retention. Funding includes the domestic dismantling of ships, contract administration of dismantling contracts, environmental surveys,
vessel disposal preparations, and unmooring for disposal which may be accomplished over multiple years.

Ships typically begin the inactivation process at the commencement of the inactivation availability. Ships are decommissioned when removed from active status. Once
decommissioned, ships remain in an inactivate status for retention, material reutilization, or pending disposal.

Ship disposal is accomplished by several methods including:
-Dismantle
-Interagency Government Transfer
-Foreign Military Sales (FMS)
-Donation
-Fleet Training (Weapons Effects Tests and Sinking Exercise).

Nuclear-Powered Ship and Submarine Inactivation
Responsible for all technical, environmental, and international treaty requirements associated with the safe and responsible inactivation and disposal of U.S. Navy nuclear-powered
ships. Nuclear-powered ships and submarines typically take several years between inactivation and decommission. They are placed in an in commission, in reserve status as of the
date of the start of their inactivation availability and decommissioned upon release of the crew following fuel removal. Nuclear-powered ships and submarines take years to fully
dispose and recycle.

This program includes all aspects of nuclear-powered ship inactivation and disposal including:

-Advance Planning
Funds the development shipyard dry-dock schedules, availability work schedules and key events, engineering and design drawings, surveys, nuclear training of defueling team,
material procurement, and demilitarization methodology and identification.

-Inactivation without Reactor Compartment Disposal (RCD) and Hull Recycling

       410                                                                                                                                                  Exhibit OP-5, 2B2G$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 410, 427, $$d7ce430d160018bc084dd11f2b1cd12145605e992496bee995b497d500c4bf3c$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1c4c$$, 2027, $$This budget line funds the intellectual foundation of naval combat power. While other line items maintain our ships and weapons, the "Warfare Tactics" line item sharpens the
mind of the warfighter. It directly funds the development, validation, and teaching of the advanced Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures (TTPs) that allow our Sailors to turn
steel ships and advanced systems into decisive combat effects. This investment is the primary driver behind the Fleet's tactical proficiency, ensuring our forces can out-think,
out-maneuver, and out-fight any adversary. By funding the Navy's Warfare Development Centers (WDCs), this line item generates the "combat software" for the human-in-the-
loop, delivering a high-leverage return on investment that multiplies the effectiveness of the entire Fleet.

Doctrine & Combat Tactics Development — Writing the Playbook for Victory
 This funds the intellectual core of the Navy's warfighting capability. It is the tactical innovation hub for combat effectiveness, supporting the expert personnel who create,
 validate, and publish the official tactical guidance that enables the entire fleet to fight as a unified and lethal force. This funding allows our Warfare Development Centers to
 analyze adversary threats, assess our own capabilities, and develop the formal combat "playbook" used to counter peer competitors. It also supports the development of
 specialized tactics for irregular warfare and global integration, ensuring the Navy has the intellectual edge across the full spectrum of conflict. In short, this pillar funds the
 brainpower that allows the Navy to out-think and out-maneuver any potential foe.

Advanced Tactical Training — Forging Combat-Ready Teams
 This funding takes the "playbook" developed by the doctrine and combat tactics efforts and turns it into proven combat proficiency. Funding here supports the direct execution
 of high-end, integrated training events that certify our deploying forces are ready for high-end conflict. It enables the readiness and training cells at our major Atlantic and
 Pacific Fleet commands to prepare forces for advanced exercises. This funding is critical to our premier training organizations, Strike Group Four (CSG-4) on the East Coast
 and Strike Group Fifteen (CSG-15) on the West Coast, which lead our Carrier Strike Groups and Amphibious Ready Groups through their final, complex certification events.
 This pillar also sustains the Navy Continuous Training Environment (NCTE), a vital network that connects our live and virtual assets across the globe, allowing our forces to
 train as they would fight.

Fleet Experimentation, & Wargaming — Designing the Navy of Tomorrow
  This funds the essential physical infrastructure and assets required to train, test, and experiment. This funding operates and sustains the Navy's bi-coastal, instrumented, live-
  fire training ranges, providing safe and realistic environments for the entire fleet. It specifically supports the major Atlantic Fleet Range Complexes, including the Virginia
  Capes and the Jacksonville Shallow Water Training Range, and the major Pacific Fleet Range Complexes, including the Pacific Missile Range Facility in Hawaii and the
  Southern California offshore ranges. This pillar also procures, maintains, and deploys a wide variety of aerial and surface targets that give our sailors a realistic "bullseye" to
  aim at, allowing us to validate our weapon systems and train our operators during exercises in these ranges.
  A critical function of this pillar is to ensure the combat readiness of the Marine Corps' aviation component as a key element of the Naval Force. This funding specifically
  addresses the unique, advanced training requirements of Marine Aviation, which occur outside the Navy's standard fleet readiness cycle. It provides the resources for the
  readiness-building exercises directed by the Deputy Commandant for Aviation, including the world-renowned Weapons and Tactics Instructor (WTI) Course run by Marine
  Aviation Weapons and Tactics Squadron One (MAWTS-1), unit-level training for the Marine Aircraft Wings, and large-scale, combined arms exercises. By funding the use of
  ranges, targets, and exercise control groups for these events, we ensure our Marine expeditionary forces can hone their skills and certify their readiness to project power from
  the sea.

Lessons Learned & Fleet Analysis — Ensuring a Continuous Learning Cycle
  This funds the critical "so what" functions that measure fleet performance and ensure the Navy is a true learning organization. It is the feedback loop that keeps our tactics
  relevant and drives continuous improvement. Funding supports the systematic collection of objective data from exercises and real-world operations, allowing for rigorous, fact-
       211                                                                                                                                                  Exhibit OP-5, 1C4C$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 211, 227, $$b75b1464f6295a44ce0a4e493ecc5580b531a3ab79d9ea46b81a0f7f6bf5080b$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
INSERT INTO public.om_sag_narratives (sag_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$om_navy_active_1a5a$$, 2027, $$A. Airframe Rework: This program provides Fleet aircraft inspection, rework and emergent repairs. Through periodic depot level maintenance activities, aircraft major structures
and airframe systems are maintained in a safe flyable condition. Depot maintenance is currently being performed under the Integrated Maintenance Concept (IMC), Phase Depot
Maintenance (PDM) and other scheduled and unscheduled depot maintenance programs. The IMC concept uses Planned Maintenance Intervals (PMI), performing depot
maintenance, with smaller work packages, reducing out of service time. The program's goal is to improve readiness and availability while reducing operating and support costs.
Currently, the AV-8B, C-130, C-2, E-2, EA-18G, FA-18, H-1, H-53, H-60, MV-22, and P-3 and P-8 are supported under IMC. The PDM concept is used with the E-6B, F-16 and
Executive Helicopter aircraft. MQ-4, MQ-8, other cargo, test pilot and trainer aircraft programs are supported under other scheduled rework programs.

B. Engine Rework: The engine rework program accomplishes aircraft engine, engine modules, gearboxes and torque meters repair and overall. The program objective is to return
depot-repairable engines to ready-for-issue (RFI) status to support Fleet aircraft and Fleet engine pool requirements. Under the Reliability Centered Maintenance (RCM) Program
engines are repaired at the lowest level of maintenance possible. Engines beyond the intermediate maintenance activities repair capability are scheduled for depot induction.
Engine field team is included in this budget submission to provide on-site depot level maintenance on an as-needed basis.

C. Components: The component repair program supports depot level aircraft mission systems and equipment component repair under programs and projects that do not have a
Material Support Date (MSD) established. Additionally, Contractor Logistics Support (CLS) support is provided for closed-loop weapon systems and equipment for Presidential
Helicopter and trainer aircraft propeller repair that will be commercially supported for its life cycle.

D. Depot Readiness Initiative – AVDLR: The Depot Readiness Initiative (DRI) utilizes depot capacity (i.e. skilled depot level artisans) to accomplish select Organizational level
(O-level) tasks (repairs, inspections, technical directive incorporation, etc.) into Phased Depot Maintenance (PDM) and Planned Maintenance Interval (PMI) events. This initiative
expedites the delivery of a Mission Capable (MC) aircraft to the squadron following a depot event. O-level DRI maintenance events may include special inspections, phase/hourly
inspections, Technical Directives (TDs), ordering the non-RFI component replacements and unscheduled maintenance (over and aboves.)

E. Calibration: The Calibration program is the sole method utilized to sustain required in-service measurement of Test, Measurement and Diagnostic Equipment (TMDE) and
Aviation Support Equipment (SE) accuracy. This equipment is used to test, repair, and maintain aircraft, Aviation Weapon Systems, and other measurement-based performance
verifications. This program establishes and maintains Calibration Laboratory Reference Standards (CALSTDs) and supporting technical products/services to ensure aviation
measurement parameters are traceable and accurate to US National standards held at the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST). Program funds sustain aviation 'I'
and 'D' level cal lab capability, and 'D' level man-hours for asset cal beyond Fleet capability. Calibration is an on-cycle maintenance action for all quantitative equipment, which
must be removed from service if left un-calibrated.

F. Ground Support Equipment Rework: The SE Rework Program provides the management, facilities, equipment, material, and manpower to perform Depot Level
Maintenance for Aviation Support Equipment.

G. Aviation Mobile Facilities: The Aviation Mobile Facilities program supports Aviation Mobile Facility configurations for the Navy and Marine Corps.

A Mobile Facility (MF) is a tactical shelter that meets structural and dimensional requirements of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the American National
Standards Institute (ANSI), and the American Society for Testing and Material (ASTM). Designed for a 20-year service life. MFs are heated and cooled by Environmental Control
Units. All configuration of units is completed at Maintenance Depot Marine Core Base in Albany, Georgia. Occasional MF and equipment rework is performed at Blount Island
Command for the USMC Maritime Prepositioning Ships (MPS) program.

       85                                                                                                                                                     Exhibit OP-5, 1A5A$$, $$$$, NULL, $$O&M/FY27/Navy/OMN_Book.pdf$$, 85, 94, $$94f720b885335ca6d0960453204b330447d94569ac64d455027e3c4d042c5828$$, $$2026-05-09T23:43:48.682814+00:00$$) ON CONFLICT DO NOTHING;
